\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}44 Morwell Avenue{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Marital status - you're a widow?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 I'm a widow - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And the year of your marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 1916.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And of your birth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 19 - 1891.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And the birthplace?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, I was born in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Oxford{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Whereabouts in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Oxford{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Kings Terrace.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 How many years did you live in that house in King's Terrace? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh now that I couldn't say - it was 1891 I was born. I think I was the last one down that way then they came - to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}George Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - where the New Theatre is. My two younger - but those two boys - the last two boys were born in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}George Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 So it would have had to have been sometime in 1894 probably?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you remember why the family moved to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}George Street
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, I don't - unless it was to get larger accommodation.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Was it a larger place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 It was a nice house. Overlooking the High School - that's pulled down now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 How long did you stay there in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}George Street{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh we were there a good number of years because we had two houses in there - we l
ived in this one up by the High School and then lower down. And we moved - we moved from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}George Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Paradise Square{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Before the end of the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. We were there when war broke out - yes. We were in - no, we were in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Paradise Square{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} when war broke out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you think you had been there long?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, I shouldn't think so. Round about 1910 or '12. Something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Now the first place you lived in in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}George Street
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} was that where the municipal restaurant now is?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
No. No, it was higher up by the High School and it was up between the shops and in a big courtyard and just this one house - quite a big house. But just a front yard, you know, no garden or anything like that - at the back of the houses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you know why you moved from that one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Well, probably because it was going to be pulled down to make an extension for the High School you see, it was more or less connected there in some way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And when you moved to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Paradise Square{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} why was that move do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, I don't know, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 At the end of the war was the family still in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}
Paradise Square{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} or had they moved again - do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, they - we'd all dispersed by then you see - we'd married - I had a - a sister gone away to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
Southampton{\*\xmlclose} - she was manageress of one of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 Kadema}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
 branches and she would be moved. She first was moved to Bedford and from there she went to Southampton and - one sister went to London to the Arsenal on munitions during the first world war, one went nursing 
and - was out in France the whole of the war - winning the military medal as well, by the way, and my brothers of course were all in the Army, but they were married and away from home you see. But - all five brothers were in the army.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And had your father and mother passed away by then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
No, my - no, oh no my mother came up here to live with me finally - she lived 'til ninety-one. My father died in - 1917 and he was eighty-eight when he died. I always know because my first child was born in 1918 in
 May and my father died the previous October, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Was he an {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Oxford{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} person?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. Yes. Yes, born in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Oxford{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, but I couldn't say where, but I do remember seeing his birth certificate once amongst my mothers papers and - he was the son of a carpenter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What was his job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Well, in early years he was a guard on the railway - I have a picture of him there - but as the years went on he adjusted - all sorts of odd jobs you know. He - he helped at - Archer Coutey and Co. and Saunders removing 
furniture and so on - things like that. And occasionally he worked at College. I remember {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Corpus Christi{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}College
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - he was there doing something - I couldn't tell you what, but I used to have to take his meals down - that's all I remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 When he did these odd jobs did he sort of hire himself out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. Just casual. Yes, just a casual.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What sort of age do you think he was when he started doing the casual jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, to me he was always an old man, you see, in those days people looked so much older - he always wore a beard and .....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 He was about fifty when you were born wasn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. He must have been you see when I remember him he must have been - sixty to seventy you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And you think he retired from the railways then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Well, I don't know - I'm not - no, I couldn't say. We - we sort of didn't know much about our - not so much about our parents jobs as the children do today you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Things weren't discussed so much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, no they weren't - it was very different wasn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You don't know then what he did before he was a guard or if that would have been his life's work up until then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You wouldn't know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, I wouldn't know that. I - I only have a picture of him in a - a guards un
iform - I want those painted - I'll show it to you presently.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you ever remember him being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes. Yes. There was a lot of - that's why my mother had to work at the machine you see - my mother was a tailoress as I told you and she
 had to work quite hard to keep us. There were a lot of us you know. Things were - things were hard but - comparing with the things today I don't think we did too badly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Was she from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Oxford{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. But she was actually born at - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Milton{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 Shipton-under-Wychwood}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
 because her father was a policeman you see and as you know they get moved. County police.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you know if she was a tailoress before she married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And when she worked after she was married it was on sort of piece-work at home was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What they used to call outside work - you see you had to go and fetch it, you took your completed work in and brought out some more.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 She didn't go to work in a factory or work-shop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Could you hazard a guess at how many hours she spent on that work in a day or a week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, she seemed to be always at work because it seemed to be necessary, you know, mother was always at the machine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Through the day and evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, right into - and right int
o the night sometimes you know - after we were gone to bed. But - I - of course it was very - poor pay as to what it is today but - how it did compare well I couldn't say that much you see, I was the youngest of the family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 While she was doing this work you didn't have anybody to look after you I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh no. No. The older ones looked after the younger ones you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Could you tell me how many rooms there were in that house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 Well, there were three bedrooms and box room upstairs - the
 little box room - it was one of those little rooms that has no door and one of my sisters - there was just room for a bed and a chair in there - one of my elder sister - the one that was a nurse - she had that with a curtain down instead of a door. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And th
ere were two rooms downstairs and - a sort of kitchen place - more of a - we called it the wash-house because - it had no tap inside the house there - there was one tap between two houses and a lavatory right at the bottom of the yard there. We did have o
u
r own lavatories but only the one tap. So that when my mother did the washing in one of the old fashioned stone coppers - you know - to boil the water everything had to be fetched from the tap outside. And our coal - when we had coal you see - that all ha
d to be brought through the house - through the room into the yard. Very different.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And in this house did you say one of the downstairs rooms was the wash-house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you have a front room or parlour?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, we had a front room and a
 back room. A sitting room and a living room and we had the - a - an oven grate where my mother did the cooking - in that room you see, we had our meals and everything in there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 In the living room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And the front room - was it used for special occasions or what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 It was always in use.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 It wasn't a Sunday room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
It wasn't a - oh no, it wasn't a parlour in the day - in the meaning of parlour like some people do keep it you know. No, everybody - everybody used to go in there and dump all their toys and clothes and things like that you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did anyone besides you and your own immediate family live in that house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No lodgers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh no, there was no room for anything. When we had an uncle of mine - he was in
 the Metropolitan Police and he occasionally came down to London - to Oxford - they just made him up a - a bed on the couch in the front room you see - that was the only }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 accommodation}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  we had. Unless the boys were away. If the boys were away at any time then we could put up Uncle Tom but otherwise that - he just had to sleep rough.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did your mother pay anyone to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did she do the washing at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Nothing was sent out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 It was always two days. First day for coloureds and second day for whites - or vice versa you see. Two days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Consecutive days would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Monday and Tuesdays always washing days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Can you remember whether she made your clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. Yes, she did - she made everythin
g. The boys suits - when they were small - my two younger brothers. But of course the older boys she probably had made theirs before my time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What about buying clothes - do you remember her buying anything in the way of clothes for her family?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 Yes, there used to be a shop in Queen Street - Fayer }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8405808 &}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid795503\charrsid13250951  Co. - next to Babcocks and - my mother - after she finished working for the factory she worked for the - for a tailor you see, she would do tailoring work and she used to work for Mr. Fayer and she use
d to buy lengths of cloth and stuff like that from him to make our clothes with.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did she ever buy anything ready-made?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. Well, I should think very seldom. I do remember I had a very special dress. My sister and I - I - my mother bought some re
d material - beautiful we thought it was you know and I remember we had - I had puff velvet sleeves and that was put out to be made and that's the only thing that I can remember was ever put out to be made to a Miss Nicholas - I remember my mother made ev
e
rything else for us. And then you see as my elder sister - one sister went into service - the eldest one, she went out to domestic service but the other three - the next three - they went to work at Lucas's factory you see so therefore they made everythin
g. Their underclothes and mine and my...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 They did things for you as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes, they made all the - everything for everybody between them - themselves and my mother you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 That must have been a help to your mother?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. And in t
he first world war I - they wanted people to make shirts for soldiers and my mother used to do some of those. We used to fetch the stuff from the town hall and they were made at home and taken back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Was this for Government contract?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you ever remember having any secondhand clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
No. Only - only that I had the older ones cut down. I always had the cut-me-downs and no I can't remember - well, I can remember mother going to rummage sales and places like that to get things for us but - how she dressed us was this way. You know 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Cape{\*\xmlclose} }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8405808 &}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
 Co. Limited - well we had clothing cards there. You paid so much a week on cards whatever you could afford - threepence or sixpence and then at the end of the year for every shilling that you had
 on your card they gave you a penny discount - so you had quite a nice little bit to spend. And my mother clothed us that way every year you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Was the Co-op then in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Oxford{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, but - they didn't have - a clothing shop that I can remember so early as that it was just the grocery you see. No it was 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Capes{\*\xmlclose} that clothed us - and there used to be a shop where Cooper's is now - top of St Taylor shoe shop - that was where we would shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What about repairs to shoes - where were they done?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 W
ell, with - when we lived in the house up - higher up - the man on the front was a bootmaker - the shop on the front so we always took our }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 boot mending}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  there you see or my father would do it you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 He did it did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. He had one of those iron feet and last thing you know. Oh yes, he used to re-sole the shoes and things for us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did he do anything in the way of cleaning or cooking or washing-up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes, he did all the cooking - yes. Yes, when he was home. And when he was home or 
out of a job or after he'd finished the job he would - he would do all the cooking.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 When you say he did it would your mother tell him what to do or would he just take it on himself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh, he'd just take it upon himself. My mother would buy the st
uff you see or send us up to the market. We dealt in the covered market in those days - I still do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Things like cleaning did he do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Always cleaned the windows and he always made the fire - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What about decorating or improvements to the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Well, no, not very much. He wasn't - he wasn't very much of that but he always - we always had clean windows - that was one thing he was very particular with. But he used to go to the College you see and clean windows and odd jobs like tha
t sometimes. They did in those days you see they hadn't got the number of College servants that they have today. And - well, then of course the majority of the Colleges are cleaned by contract now - window cleaners. There weren't those people in those day
s - they were only the odd job men you see. And beating carpets and things like that, they used to - oh yes, take up the carpet and - bring them on an old wheelbarrow and take them down to the top of the canal - the cut we used to call it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And give them a beating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, or take them up onto port Meadow some of the men used to you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Can you remember any other things he did there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 Well I remember there was a solicitor - there were solicitors in Cornmarket Street, Hazell }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8405808 
&}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951  Baine - they'
re now gone I believe - and he - he had a more or less a contract for cleaning their windows, so many times a year you know and whatever else he was doing he would always fit it in - he always cleaned their windows for them. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And of course there were a lot of men used to do that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Do you remember him ever when you were a small child and your two brothers dressing you or bathing you or putting you to bed - doing any of that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, but he always got it ready.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Got the bath ready?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
He always got the bath ready and fetched the water in and - we had to have the copper lighted you see for hot water - for a lot of hot water - for a weekly bath - it was a weekly bath in those days. Yes, that was in the wash house you see a
nd as all the water had to be fetched from outside - yes, he used to do all that and get it ready and then we did ourselves or one of the older ones came to see to us you see and - if my mother wasn't available but mother was always there. That was the fi
rst thing that - when we opened the door to come home you know - where's mother - that was always the first thing. It isn't like the latchkey children of today. Yes, it wasn't home if mother wasn't there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 This regular bath was it always a set night or just roughly once a week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Generally Friday and Saturday you see with a lot of - yes, just about weekly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And what about clean sets of clothing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes, we had those every week bath night, you know. And - of course if any of us fell in the c
anal, which we sometimes did, we'd have a fresh lot or else if there wasn't enough to go round - if we hadn't got enough change, you see, we had to have somebody else's to sit in for a while. I remember my sister falling in the canal. We used to go fishin
g then you see with a - a jam jar and a - a net, and we often fell in the river.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Can you ever remember him reading to you or telling you stories, that sort of thing?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, he used to sit and read to us and we - we had a very favourite - rag book
, one of the Dean's rag books which you don't see about now, and - my favourite one in that was always the - the - monkey and persimmon tree - I never knew what the persimmon was, you know, in those days - but I do now. But that was my favourite - yes, he
 did used to read to us. He was very fond of reading himself. Oh yes, and he always kept up to - with the paper with all the news - he always knew what was going on - in the world you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 He bought a daily paper did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, I expect he did 'c
os they were only a ha'penny you see in those days. Yes, we used to have a daily paper. Oh, I know we had - I knew we had the daily paper delivered by - well, you know, the men used to come round with - not exactly delivering it like they do today and put
 it in your letter box - they used to come round calling with the papers and you went out and bought one. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 
I do remember that that we had one of those regularly because at Christmas time there was always a little collection for the paper man - it was only a 
shilling but between us all we put pennies or ha'pennies whatever we'd got you see, always a shilling Christmas box for the paper man, I do remember that. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
And - and the baker and the milkman - they all had a little Christmas box - it was the regular thing to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you remember what paper it was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. I wouldn't know - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you remember him taking you out anywhere without your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, generally went all together. Sundays especially. We all had to go to church Sunday morning, you see, Sunday school and on to church.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 That was just in ....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Yes, yes. And it's the church that stands there now you see we had a - there was an opening through to the school in those days. The schools pulled down and - pulled down and rebuilt for St Peters College you see now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you ever remember you mother going out and your father being in charge of you in the home at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, yes, she used to go along - I had an auntie living here at Marston that I remember most and - she used to t
ake the younger ones along there to Auntie Bolter's. Mrs Bolter her name was - but she was always called Auntie Bolter and then you see when we went home - where's mother? Always - or where's mum - it was mainly mum - and - my father would say oh she's go
ne to see your Auntie Bolter - she won't be home yes, and he would always get out tea - our tea was always ready there when we came home from school you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 He would have got it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you have any regular jobs to do in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes, clean the knives and we rubbed them on a board. A board - a board with bathbrick - that was a Saturday morning job - clean the knives and forks - we had a leather to clean the forks with and the knives had to be rubbed on board you see and t
he spoons had - two leathers, we had a - one for putting - the bathbrick on - one that you wetted and one that you dried them with. And then the boys - they would have to clean the shoes or - scrub the steps. We had - two - three steps leading up to the f
r
ont - two steps leading up to the front door. That - right onto the street, you see, and the boys had to clean the - and fetch the coal from the coal merchants and things like that. But my father always cleaned the windows - and we had beautiful clean win
dows always 'cos he was so particular about them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
You were saying how later on the older girls made clothes and things for the younger ones - do you remember anything else that the older children did to help you and your younger brothers when you were little - anything they did for you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Well, only that they sort of more or less looked after us and fetched us in from play - teatimes or evenings and - and helped us get ready for bed - washed us and put us to bed. Oh yes. And - also you see they use
d to sit at home - they each had a machine which they bought on the hire purchase system, I might tell you, and this week I went to see my sister that's eighty-eight and she'd still got her machine and - they used to make clothes for other people - underc
l
othes and things you see for other people. Especially - if - someone was getting married they would make all the trousseau - two sets of everything you know. And of course it was all embroidery in those days. Very fancy - a lot of work in it. I don't know
 how much they charged but - they used to earn a few extra shillings you see that way for their own clothes then you see so they could dress a bit better.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 That was extra to their factory working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. For their factory work - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Can you remember doing anything for them - when you were little?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Well only by going errands and things like that you know. We might - and - oh one thing I used to do and that was when they made these fancy - knickers and camisoles and things like that I used t
o help them by threading the ribbon through and finishing off. Buttonholes - I was very good at buttonholes. Oh yes, we all helped each other you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Were you expected to be in bed at a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes, at home and in bed - generally eigh
t o'clock. But - never out - outside the house - never out of doors after half past eight to nine - if we were out after nine o'clock my goodness we got into trouble.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Were other children in those days around as late as that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes, lots of chil
dren and we used to - our playground then was Gloucester Green - which is the car park now. And used to be a cattle market you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Was there also the other cattle market too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. No. It was the cattle market there and of course all the beasts were brought in by road. Walking in. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 Because I remember often - when they had cattle in there - and you see the beasts that had to be walked in the morning and they needed milking before they could go back and we were sent with a big jug and for that - for 
tuppence - we had a big jug of milk straight from the cow. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
You see the farmers were glad to relieve the cows of it and we were glad to have it. Oh yes. It was quite - we were - had a happy childhood really, you know, for working class people - oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 I don't think their childhood was any more unhappy than the others do you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, oh no. I mean we didn't have a lot of money but - we had a good home - had a good home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Your older sisters used to put you to bed did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did your mother sometimes put you to bed too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. But if mother was - wanted to finish off some tailoring or anything like that you see - oh yes, they would do that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Can you remember about what age you started to put yourself to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, I suppose I must have been about ten - eleven, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What were the sleeping arrangements of the family in that house?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well now, going upstairs there was mother and dad and the two boys - two youngest boys. Babies they were - one -
 there was a cot and a sort of a chair bed. In the room at the back were the two older boys - Ben and Charlie because Harry was gone into the Army. And - Nell was gone into domestic service. And so in the two top bedrooms - there was the little box room y
ou see with Edith and then in the other room were two beds. And two - two of us slept in each bed. There was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 Maggie and May, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
the twins in one and myself and Florence in the other.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Didn't you say there were three bedrooms altogether or were there two bedrooms and the box}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid795503\charrsid13250951  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, three bedrooms and the box}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 room - that was .....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 So one there was four of you girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 In another was your parents and the two little boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 One girl. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And then there was the one girl in the little box}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Mm. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 
And the two boys in the back bedroom - behind the - behind the parents' room you see on the first floor.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Can you remember when the boys got older did they stay on - the younger boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, the two younger boys - wel
l you see by the time the two younger boys had grown up the two older boys had gone. You see the elder one had gone into the Army - in the regular Army he was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 That was Henry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. That was Henry - he was in the Lifeguards - he went into the Arm
y as they called it in those days. And then Ben and Charlie you see they were working and eventually got married and then of course the two younger boys went into their room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 The family ate in the living room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Were there any occasions when you ate in the other room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Well, sometimes yes. If we had - company come or my aunties or anything of that came you see, some of us would have to go in there because - the rooms were not all that big. But we didn't keep it specially to sort of l
ook at you know. We took care of it - we had to. I mean we couldn't just go in there and - play about and pull the place about - we had to be careful with it. There was a little better furniture in there of course but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 When you went in there when company came would it be an overflow room - would other children be eating in the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes, in the - in the other room - or we would - yes, we would take it into there - we had to take it into there you see - sat up the other table that we had in
 there and - part of us have our tea in there and part in the other room. We all had to sit to table - there was no running about with food - oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Your mother cooked in the living room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What sort of cooking equipment did she have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Just this coal oven at the side. And everything was cooked in there - prepared out in the outer place - in the washhouse place - you see, vegetables and things like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Was that two ovens or one that she had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh, only the one. Then the ot
her was the - pot boiling you see on the top - yes. And we - in those days you know - a lot of the cooking was done on a jack. We had a jack and my father - it was clockwork you see - and my father wound it up and that went so many times round that way an
d
 then so many times back again and it hung down and there was a trivet in front of the fire - hitched onto the fire grate you see, and the - the dish was there to catch the fat and every so often you see we had to baste the meat with it - with the fat and
 
then pot - then the potatoes were put into the fat and they were cooked in the oven. And the puddings you see always cooked in the oven but all the other vegetables were cooked on top of the open fire - there was no gas stove in there in those days. But -
 
lovely. And we used to have what we call a dutch oven. You don't see those now - but - my father used to like herrings - bloaters done that way - in front of the fire on the - in the dutch oven. It - the dutch oven was an oven like that with a - side you 
see and that would come up like that and all this part would be exposed to the fire and there'd be a row of hooks along there which you put your meat on or whatever you had on there and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 It would get the heat that way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. And then you see we took it round the other way and opened up the other side.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did that other side also have hooks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Yes. Well, it was the one - the one things with the two sort of sides - two legs. Well it would - sort of go over that way - you turned it round you see, and then you could bring it back and do that side.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 I've never seen one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Haven't you. I've sold many, many one at - where I worked you see we used to sell them wholesale. Dutch ovens - they used to be - yes, we always had a dutch oven. We used
 to do toast on there like that sometimes you see, it was a little bit longer but my father used to love - a bloater or herring done that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you have them at tea or breakfast - these bloaters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, some - my father used to like one teatim
es because - when he wasn't working - he - sort of didn't bother about a meal with us at mid-day - he looked after us and got ours and washed all up and everything you see if my mother was machining. But when he was working of course that was different - 
h
e had his - he always had his meal when he came home - whatever time it was. If my mother was expecting him at a certain time then she'd get his meal ready and it would be put into the oven you see until he came in. It was always cut off the same time as 
o
urs and put onto a plate and then kept and put into the oven when it was time for him to come home. Or - I - I do remember - there used to be a very nice little restaurant up where - close to the corn exchange in George Street where you could take your ow
n
 plates and get a good dinner on a plate for sixpence. Because when my brothers were on the engine - you know I told you they went on the traction engine first - when they were coming home late - see if there wasn't enough to save for them from lunchtime,
 or if we had something different - we would be sent along there with two plates and you had a sixpenny dinner put on there, you see, came home and that was put into the oven ready for the boys}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1320587\charrsid13250951  when }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 they came in. And a good dinner it was too. Meat and two veg usually a little bit of}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13250951  }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 York}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 -shire pudding - something like that. And it was really good - really good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did people go and eat there as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you do that in your family?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, no, we didn't do that. We fetched it if the boys - if mother hadn't got enough for the boys you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 She would always make up with two sixpenny dinners, from Vin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1320587\charrsid13250951 t\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 
 it was in those days - Mr Vin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1320587\charrsid13250951 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 .}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 About what time would breakfast be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well - we always had a scramble for school so I expect it was more or less a moveable feast - you know - standing up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 It wasn't an organised sort of meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
No. No, there was so many of us you see - we were all called and some got up and some didn't and some were late for school - well, not very of
ten we were not allowed to be late because if it meant being late for school you just had to go without any breakfast you see. That was usually a cup of tea, bread and butter, toast - nothing like they have today you know, with cereals and things like tha
t. But - always - some bacon for Sunday. Always - and sometimes an egg - either an egg or bacon but - always a little bit of bacon for Sundays. That was the only time we had a cooked - a cooked - breakfast - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Was your father there at breakfast time or had he usually gone out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 
If - if he was working you see, but of course in my sort of later days - he didn't do so much regular work so that he was always home, but he was always cooking and getting ready for us and - and -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Sounds wonderfully helpful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh he was - yes. He used to - he used to like doing it - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What about mid-day - you had your main meal then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. Yes. And it was always more or less ready when we came - went in from school you see. Some of us had to go 
and do errands for different people. At - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 in}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  the school - mid - in the school break you see. So that -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, I did. I used to - I used to earn threepence a week by going to the covered market every Friday morning and carrying hom
e twelve pounds of liver and fat for the lady that kept the shop across the way - I carried home twelve pounds of liver and fat and I ordered so many sets of hocks and - pigs hocks and feet for her to cook and sell during the weekend. For that she gave me
 threepence and the shop that I went to in the market - Mr Harold Martin - he always gave me a penny. So that was my wages.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 That was just once?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Once a week - Fridays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 How old were you when you started doing that - can you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, I - I guess I must have been about ten or eleven because you see I went to work when I was thirteen and it was before then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Quite a weight really for a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 It was - yes. But I had it in one of those big fish bags you know - and I managed all right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And that was in the lunch hour was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, that was Friday mornings before I went to school. Yes, and I always had to get up earlier on Friday morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What did you do with the money?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Spent it. No, I - well, I had to save i
t - we all had money boxes and they were wooden money boxes and my father used to - he'd make a little slot at the - in the end that - like a little door thing you know - but that was pasted over - woe betide us if we broke it you know. We had to put the 
money in and leave it in for so long or Christmas or a fair we had to save up for St Giles }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1320587\charrsid13250951 F}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
air you see. And then it - when they were opened - my father always opened them and they would see how much we'd got in and if we'd got quite a few shillings we had 
to buy something with it in the way of clothes or give it to my mother towards buying us clothes and shoes and things you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 So it was put in there first - it wasn't just spent on sweets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes, it was - oh no. We could spend a penny or somet
hing like that - a portion of it you see but we were never given threepence all at once to spend. But I think we appreciated it you know. And then - there was a Miss Gardner who lived up the street and she was a wonderful embroiderer in those days you kno
w the college badges here and the caps were all done by hand and she used to work for the different university shops and I had sixpence a week there for taking home work after school that was - after four o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You took it from her place to the shops?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 
In a nice little covered basket - had to be very careful with it because it was most beautiful work you see.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 How often was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh two and three times a week - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 So you did quite well really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 I did very well - yes. About ninepence a week you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 On the question of meals - was the mid-day meal always a hot meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Yes, because I - I remember one of our favourite dinners was a large bullocks heart and - that was stuffed with seasoning and roasted with lots of
 potatoes round it and a good hefty suet pudding with it and we had that sliced with thick gravy and the potatoes and that one day and the next day it was hashed up with lots of vegetables into a stew. That was one of my favourite meals. Made us hefty you
 know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well it was very nourishing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Well, it was. And of course it was reasonable for price no doubt. In those days you - you had one of those very large hearts for about half-a-crown or two and nine you see. Well, if that made two meals for four
 or five children it was very good. Plenty of potatoes and vegetables you see. We always fed very well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Was there a pudding most days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, if we were not going to have a sweet pudding which was usually one that could be done in the oven - a ri
ce pudding of sago or something like that - we would have a suet pudding with the meat course you see - a plain suet pudding - like you make dumplings and you had it in a cloth and then the next day when there wasn't quite so much meat - not quite so much
 first course we had a spotted dick generally you see - a current duff - or something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 That suet pudding - would you have that with the meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You never had your pudding first?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. But, you see, sometimes we would have the suet pudding and sometimes we would have a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 Yorkshire}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  pudding. Have either one or the other you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you remember how often in the week you'd have meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, there weren't many - very many days that we didn't get - that we went withou
t meat of some sort. Some days it was more plentiful than others, I mean when you had the joint first of all but the second time you didn't get quite such bit helpings but there was enough - oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you ever remember you mother buying tinned meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
No. Well, there wasn't much about. But - I can remember her buying corned beef in the tins - you bought them in the pound tins like they do now. And - slicing them up for sandwiches for my brothers to take when they went out on the traction engines. 
And - they were....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Tinned vegetables or fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
No, no. No, never. We used to - we used to fetch our vegetables from the places in the covered market and you see the potatoes and - well everything - was sold then by the quarten, you didn't buy t
hem by the pound like you do now. They were in the quarten measures - half a peck and quarten and peck. You bought a peck of potatoes at a time you see. Yes. And you bought a peck of broad beans or a peck of peas - you didn't buy a pound.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 I don't suppose you were able to grow any vegetables and fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. We never had places with gardens you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Everything was bought that you had in that way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What about extra meat from sources like poaching - did you ever have anyone give you anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 We did have an occasional rabbit sometimes I can remember. Where it came from I don't know. One thing I do remember were crayfish. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 We had an uncle who lived out on the Bleinham estates and the river Glane there you know - a
 lot of crayfish there and my Uncle Charlie used to bring us in a - a bundle of crayfish - a box of crayfish which he'd poached. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 'Cos he'd poach them. That's - I don't remember -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you enjoy them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, we did. Yes we did. And there used to be 
a man come round - selling mushrooms you see there were fields and fields of mushrooms - not the cultivated ones like you do today - and they were yours for the picking. And some of the men used to go and pick them you see and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1320587\charrsid13250951 then}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  come and sell them and make a little money that way. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 But you don't remember actually having anything that was definitely poached?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. No. I don't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you have any relatives in the country who gave you fruit and vegetables or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, on
ly this one this one that would stop with the crayfish that we had. Oh my aunties at - at Marston here - she had a nice garden and - and gave us gooseberries and things like that you know - for treats, but I can't remember anything else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What about things like keeping hens or pigs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, there was never any room anywhere that we went, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 When you were having your meals do you ever remember your mother having less so that the rest of you could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, I dare she did because sometimes you see she'd say - no, I'll have mine when you're gone.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You were saying if you were seen talking to an undergraduate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 Well, somebody'd look down on you, you see, you were classed as not quite nice and we did used to meet them but we
 always had to meet them round the corner and when they brought us home at night they had to leave us round the corner - not be seen anywhere near our home - 'cos - yes.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did they sort of take advantage of the girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, it - well it just wasn'
t done you see. And - if the bulldogs were about you see the men daren't be seen with girls. At all. It's very different to now - very different of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you have any boyfriends who were undergraduates?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes, we did. We often did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Where did you meet them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh used to meet them round the corner or at the end of a certain street you know or something like that - but nowhere near colleges. And then we went for a walk yes - we generally went up by Port Meadow way or in those days th
e canal was much nicer than it is now - it was quite a nice walk - go down the riverside you see - used to go down the riverside. But not anywhere near the colleges. In case anyone....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And not near your own homes either?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. My goodness if my fa
ther ever knew that we were going around with under-graduates we'd have been - well, gated like they used to be you see. Oh no, we wouldn't have been allowed out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Where did you meet them originally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, just met them about the town or probably...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Get into conversation in the town you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, oh yes. And you see my sister worked - she worked at the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 Kadima}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  caf\'e9 and - they used to have a lot of boys used to go in there and they got to know quite a number of boys. Undergraduates - thr
ough going in - her customers you see then - always be a bit cheeky with one another when they came outside you know. I met my husband dancing there - we used to go dancing and ......
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Where was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Over here - at the Co-op rooms, actually. But
 - there were several little dance halls - well, there were places where you could be taught dancing you see. He worked at that time - the University Press and they had a - a club room and they taught dancing there. Sixpence we used to pay on - on a - lea
rners night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 That was a club the press workers used?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. Yes, the clar - the University press - printing press - yes. Oh yes, I learnt dancing there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 About the meals again - you were saying that you think your mother did sometimes have less?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Well, I think she must have done because - 'course there were quite a number of us round the table and - we would say 'where's yours mother? - you see or something like that. She'd say 'oh I'm going to have mine when you're gone - when there's a bi
t of peace' she would say. But of course as we've grown up we've realised that perhaps she didn't have quite so much as we did. She gave it to us first you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What about your father - in some families he had more - do you think he had more than the rest of you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
No. No. No. He was never served first. No. The children were always served first. And often mother and father would sit and have theirs after we were gone back to school you see or they would say they would so probably there wasn't quit
e so much and perhaps both of them went without a bit you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Were you allowed to talk during the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
No. No talking. 'You can't talk while you're eating' my father used to say. And he was very particular about us - never talking with our mo
uths full of food and never drinking while we still had food in our mouth - that was one thing that I notice on television nowadays - sort of bad manners. With the grown ups you see them drinking away and still eating their food and I often say to my sist
er if we're watching together - my goodness, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 that}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
 wouldn't have done for our dad would it. It wouldn't either - no - it wouldn't - we were never allowed ever to do anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Could you talk if there was something you wanted passed to you - like the cruet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes. Oh yes. Just - you could - you could just talk about different things that perhaps had happened at school, you see, pass remarks on Miss - the teacher would say so and so and my father would say 'eat your food first and tell us a
fterwards' you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 On the whole were they interested in talking to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes. Oh yes. We always told them what happened at school and of course if we had the cane my father used to say 'well I expect you deserved it'.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 He wasn't going up to the school to find out why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh no. No. My mother ......
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Was that done for some people - parents coming up to complain?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, I can't remember. In those days ever anyone did - I think most people used to say - well, we sent you to school t
o be corrected and you do as the master says. We always - whatever Mr Davies said - that was the headmaster - whatever Mr Davies said was right. And if you were sent to Mr Davie}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1320587\charrsid13250951 s}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  from the classroom by the other teachers that was a terrible disgrace.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 If your mother cooked your food and you didn't fancy something could you say no or did you have to have everything she cooked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, if you couldn't eat that then you're not hungry. So you had to eat it. Or go without.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 There was no substitute?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh there was nothing special for anybody - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 If you left something on your plate - what would she say to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 Well, we'll - always got grumbled at about leaving it but - we were never chastised for it - we always had a cat you know that wo
uld clear it up - but .....}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 It wasn't brought back the next meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh no. No, but if - my mother would say 'well if you can't eat that you're not hungry' - you see, there's nothing else and so if you were really hungry well you ate it whether you liked it or not you see. Oh dear, it is either that or starve.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Could you ask for a second helping?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes. If there was any there. It was always more or less cleared up you see at the table my mother would say - 'anyone want anymore beans or any more potatoes' and usually you see the - the dishes were finally cleared right up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What about things like how you held your knife and fork and how you sat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. Yes, indeed. You sit up to the table in the proper manner - that was my father
. Well, we were made to sit to the table and have our meals and say grace - yes - and we couldn't leave the table until we asked. Oh dear no, nothing of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you have to wait ....?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 We could go when we'd finished - we - we - were not obliged
 to wait for the others if we'd finished and there was no pudding or nothing else to come you see - but my mother didn't wait 'til everybody had finished before she served the pudding, you see, whoever finished first they had - they were served and gone a
way. No, you didn't have to wait 'til all the others had finished - but you couldn't leave the table until you had finished properly and once you'd left the table you didn't come back. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And could you bring a toy or a book to the table during a meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. No reading. No reading at table. No reading while there were meals on the table - ever. That was one thing ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And did you always have the same places?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, generally. Oh yes, because we used to fight over that you see, that's my
 place - this is my chair and that's my knife and fork. We always had our own - special things you know. I suppose we must have chosen them ourselves at some time and - and that was it, you see, because - I remember sitting down at the table - of course m
y brother had got my fork and I snaps that and had mine to give him that back - oh there was always a lot of that going on. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 The two youngest - do you remember when they were very young and not at a stage when they could feed themselves how were they fed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Generally on my mother's knee as far as I can remember. Or the elder one you see, whoever had finished first - if my - elder sister }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 Maggie}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  generally it was. She used to take the young ones. If she finished her's first you see she'd feed th
e other ones. But it was generally my mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Would you say your mother was an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Well, no, you see in those days everything was kept hidden from us. We - we - we couldn't talk like the - like the mothers and daughters do to
day - oh no, there was nothing of that. And - well, of course everything was hushed up in those days - you didn't know life as we knew it - know it now. Oh dear no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 When your young brothers were born did you think they'd come from a gooseberry bush or something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Well, no - I don't know what we thought. Nobody seemed to know, but I do remember my youngest brother being born and we had a Mrs Kitchen came in to look after my mother. I remember my mother being in bed you know and having thi
s baby and the doctor coming - but more than that - well, doctor with his little black bag sort of thing you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 If you were worried about something could you tell her about that? Or did you keep it to yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, no, I don't think - I don
't think we sort of had great worries - it was - our biggest worries perhaps were just quarrels with children at school you know and things like that - until we began to get older - the sixteen and seventeen years and that you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 You more or less learned life from some of the older people.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Older brothers and sisters do you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, yes. Of course a lot that we heard wasn't true but - we didn't sort of know at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did she show affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. Oh yes, if mother wasn't ther
e we were all terribly worried. When we went to you know. But, mind you - she was strict as well with us but - we had all the love that there could be you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And your father - would you say he also wasn't an easy person to talk to like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
No, he wasn't and he was very strict you see and the latter years of his life he used to like to go out to the public house and I think looking back on life, you know, it was a worry to my mother then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You think he went more than was good for him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
He did and he used to boast when he was in his cups as you might say, that he'd got the finest family in Oxford and his girls were the best girls you know like they all do. And I - I remember somebody telling us he boasted and he said yes they've all hi
s family - they were big fine girls and fine boys, if they were all put head to foot they'd stretch right up George Street. Silly old thing. Oh he was always very proud of us although I do remember when one of my brothers broke - a - a window through play
ing football. My father went and mended it but my brother had to pay for it - he stopped his pocket money - whatever pocket money he was getting in those days. Which of course was only like all of us - what we'd earned from various things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 But he confiscated it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. He - he - he had to pay for it you see. He had to be shown that it was wrong to do it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What kind of people do you think your parents hoped you'd grow up to be - do you think they had sort of aspirations for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, I don't think that - I don't think they -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 As far as values and that sort of thing is concerned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
No, I think that as long as we conducted ourselves properly and didn't get into any trouble that they were quite - quite sort of pleased with us you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What sort of things did they bring you up to consider important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Well, my other brother - my elder brother went into the Army you see and then - the other two boys they - they were - they worked on the traction engine and they worked at night 
at the theatre and things like that and - so long as we - they could pay their way and keep themselves out of trouble as far as - you know - the police - 'cos they got into trouble for playing football and things like that - the things most people did in 
t
hose - there weren't the playing fields of course in those days like there are now - to keep them off the streets. But we used to mainly play in Gloucester Green and the boys - although they were older than us - I mean they all had to be home at a certain
 time. Oh yes. And they had to go to Sunday school same as we others - yes, had to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Up to what age did you have to go to Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh right until I was - after I'd started work - fourteen. See, I went to work at thirteen and I'm still going to Sunday school. Oh yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 If another child hit you would your parents say you should hit back or not?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Yes. They would. They would say well you're silly to let him do it - why didn't you hit him back? But they would never come and interfere - t
hey would never come and take our part you see, if we - if we did say - as I suppose some of us might have done - well, why don't you come and see him and tell him off and because - oh no, they never did that. You had to fight your own battles - yes. And 
- and fight your own battles and keep out of battles - that was the only thing to do you see - keep away from them. If you can't - if you can't go out without fighting then stop indoors - father used to say. Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did they bring you up to behave towards your brothers and sisters in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes, we all had to behave ourselves at - especially indoors and - if some of the older ones came home telling tales and that you see my father would say 'I don't want to know - I don't want to k
now - now you fight it out and you behave yourself - I expect you when you go out to behave yourself'. So he didn't listen to-
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No tale bearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. He - he didn't listen to stories that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What did they think of swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh, it was
 dreadful. Although my father used to swear. Not to us. But in front of us he would - you know - talking about other things but we were never allowed to. And if one of them - well I remember one of them having a jolly good smack bottom - with my father}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1320587\charrsid13250951 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 s slipper. It's about the only time I can remember }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1320587\charrsid13250951 him }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 chastising them. One of them called the other a little sod and - I've never forgotten it because it was - a dreadful word to us in those days and my father never forgave them for it. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1320587\charrsid13250951 And he just took his slipper off you see, his leather slippers and walloped their bottom. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
They didn't do it again you see - cured them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 When grown ups were talking were you allowed to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh no. No. Not - your mother's talking - my father you see or my mother. 
If either of those were something and we interfered you see one of them would say 'now wait a minute your father's talking'. You could say afterwards but you must wait until your father had spoken - or your mother - what - whoever was speaking - or anyone
 that was speaking you see, we were never allowed to interrupt.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 But you could join in to a conversation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes. Oh yes. And they would listen - if you said when you were out you know - oh yes, I saw so and so - if they were talking about somebod
y and you - said - oh yes, I saw them - that was all right. But you mustn't break in to an older persons conversation, oh dear. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 If you did something they disapproved of - you remember this occasion with the slipper - do you remember any other occa
sions being punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes, they were sent up to bed. That was the punishment in those days. Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Without supper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. But - one of the others used to sneak it up you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you have supper in your family or was it just tea and nothing else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Well, we had tea and we might have after tea - if anyone had been out and was very hungry - you could have a piece of bread and butter or bread and jam or something like that but not a sit down - not a meal - no - oh no. Just a l
ittle bit to - take you up to bed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 So you'd have your tea would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And then you'd be sent up to bed as a punishment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 But you wouldn't miss your tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh no, you wouldn't miss your tea but you were sent up to 
bed. No going out any more tonight. You see, 'cos you were allowed out after tea to play out in Gloucester Green - you had to be in at a certain time - specially in the dark nights you see when it was dark - seven o'clock you came home. And if - if you we
r
en't home when it was dark woe beside you - they sent the town crier out after you, you see, all the other children were sent out to find you - do you know where so and so is - well just go and fetch her in tell her to come in you see, it used to be that.
 We were never allowed out just any old time. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 It wasn't really the town crier they sent out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Just an expression. I thought they'd gone out by then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh no, I can remember the town crier - oh yes. Oh yes. I can remember the
 man coming down shaking his bell and saying - oh yes - oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What sort of an announcement was that then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, anything lost - anything lost. And sales - they used to come round and cry out 'sale', but mainly for lost or lost children
 or property lost or something like that. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 When do you think it went out in Oxford then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh, well, I suppose it must have been before I went to work but - I suppose I must have been ten years old. I can remember them quite well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Can you remember any particular occasion when you were punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, no, I expect I - I had so many. Nothing very special - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Were the boys given the same punishment as the girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes, they were sent up to bed. Sometimes they had a tap on their bottom you know with fathers slipper to help them up but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 But not a real hiding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Would you say that you received the ideas you had about how to behave from both your parents or one more than the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. Both of them - yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 One didn't play a more important part?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh no. And one never interfered with the other. If my father said we were not to do a thing my mother never said yes you can you see. Their word was law - both of them and they didn't interfere.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No playing them off against each other?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh no. No, and there was none of this - my mother never used to say as some of the people do - ah, you wait until your father comes home, I'll tell him so and so and so and so. She dealt with us 
herself. And he dealt with us himself you see. So they never crossed each other. Well, mother .....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did she ever say I'll call a policeman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh no. She came of a police family you see. I remember - I remember my mother once - there was a - a lot 
of trouble outside - we had rather a lot of rough people at one time down there - there were lots of pubs around there in those days you see and of course they were open at all hours. In George Street especially. And I was counting them up the other day -
 
I think there were about thirteen. And - there was a - a fight out there. You see, we used to get a lot of rough men about there on the barges and places - things like that - although the majority of bargee people were very good. And there was a fight out
 there and one of the - policemen seemed to be getting into trouble and my mother went out and blew his whistle. But then you see they were - she was brought up in ....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 So the police weren't bogey men to her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh no. Definitely. Nor to us. Mind yo
u, we used to be afraid of them - they used to chase us round. There's - you know the place in Gloucester Green which is now a caf\'e9
 - in the - right - no - right in the - the - car park - in the bus station, well that place used to be used years ago as the
 settling room for the corn - for the farmers when they came to sell their beasts and things like that. It was called the settling room - they all went in there to settle up you see, and from the corn and that. Well, we used to run round to the top of tha
t when we were children and - the bobby of course used to come running after us - make us get down. So some of them had to - get him talking on this side while we others scrambled down the other side and run round there many times.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What sort of things would he be after you for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh, because we'd no business up there. We'd no business climbing up on that roof. Right on the roof on the top - boys and girls as well - simply because you see on the other side there used - which is now the ladies toilets
 and things round there - a part of that used to be the old mortuary. And we children used to think that if we got up on the top of the settling room roof you see we could see the dead people down there. And you see ....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Could you in fact?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. N
o. But they used to tease us and say we could you see and of course for devilment we used to get up there and see if we could. And then old Mr }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 Jonathon}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  Day - the man who looked after the - all these places you see - he was the Mayors Sergeant - no, Mr Beck
with was the Mayors Sergeant and you see he had a right to tell us to get down from there, we'd no business up there and occasionally of course the bobbies used to come round too and well we had to scramble down when the bobbies came. Everybody called the
m bobbies.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 How do you think they treated people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 They gave us a jolly good cuff of the head or the bottom and sent us home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 With his gloves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And their hands - and sent us home. There was no taking you - before the magistrates or anythi
ng - they dealt with you themselves. Oh yes, it would be much better if they allowed them to do it now. 'Cos I think if a policeman was allowed to give a boy just a wallop on his bottom sometimes that would cure him, and he'd go home and think no more abo
ut it, but you see they go home - they make a fuss about it and their parents take them to court which is so ridiculous and such a waste of time and money. No, the bobbies used to deal with us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 When you had a birthday in those days would it be different from any other day?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes, you always had sixpence for your birthday. Oh yes, we all, we all had our birthdays commemorated in some way - yes. Perhaps we'd have a little - special cake for tea or something like that - or be allowed a friend in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You might have a friend in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, you might have a friend in for tea, you know, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What about Christmas - do you remember doing anything with your mother and father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, we always hung our stockings up at Christmas. A
nd we always had a bright penny in the bottom and an orange and usually these sugar fancies - sugar pigs and things and I had a dolly on the top, you know, sixpenny dolly. Oh yes, my mother always - there used to be a row of stocking all along there - and
 - yes, on the fireplace where we used to have the roasting jack, you know, for the meat. That was always fixed onto a thing - on a - shelf at the top you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What did you do on Christmas Day - did you do anything together as a family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, no - only just sort of sing carols and songs and things like that - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you have a piano or any musical instruments?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You sort of sang did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, we used to sing and all the songs and the hymns from school, you know - and - and we would -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you go visiting or did anyone call round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Very seldom. We were generally all home on Christmas Day you know. But we never had a turkey or anything like that. We always had a piece of beef - generally a piece of beef - nice b
ig piece you know - and a few extras but always some crackers and things like that. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you all sing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, although I say it we were quite a musical family. We - you see, two of my brothers as I say went to work at the theatre. One - one
 was an attendant on the - well, they were both attendants on the front in the evening you see, and then my elder brother became property master there and lived in the house at the back. But when they had these musical comedies and things like that you se
e
, they always had a book of the words and songs. I believe they were about sixpence. And - and people - you see, they bought them and some of them dropped them and didn't bother to take them home and my brothers used to bring them home so we always had a 
book of words of the various things that were there - we knew all the songs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And did your mother and father sing too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 My father did. Simon the Cellarer - Simon the Cellarer - that was his favourite. Yes. Old Simon the Cellarer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What is a Cellarer - do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Works in the wine - wine cellar. Oh I can't remember the other words of it. I know that - I know the song and I often sing it - to myself. It was my fathers favourite.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 He'd sing about the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 That and the garden where the praties grow. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 He always was singing that. Praties - potatoes. It's an Irish song - it's a well known ballad - a well - known Irish ballad. Yes. "I met h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1320587\charrsid13250951 
er in the garden where the prat}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 ies grow. You must have heard it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Was your mother one to sing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, not quite so much but she used to like to go to - church and then sing the hymns like to herself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did she go regularly to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. Yes, she went - well, we all had to go. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 
But - we had - there was a man came here to the - 
Holy Trinity church which is now pulled down - and he was a man who attracted all the ladies and my mother used to go right down there - it was Blackfriars Road - it's all pulled down now - and - he ran a special meeting for men in the afternoons and anot
her afternoon it would be for women - or in the evening for women and he - he was a great attraction to the people and my mother used to go down there and think this man was wonderful. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
I can't remember his name now. He came from Blackheath in London.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What was it specially about him do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
I don't know - but he - he certainly attracted a congregation - people went from everywhere down there to him. Mm - can't remember his name.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Can you remember - your father used to get this newspaper - did you have books in the house at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. My father used to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 read}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  - quite a lot. And - one of my sisters - she's died now - she was always reading and my father used to - give her books in preference to us because she read more you see. He said she was more appreciative. I'll bet.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Where did he get them do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Well, a lot of them I think were - he used to bring them from college - what the men had discarded you see or if he was out on a moving job and - they'd thrown a lot of boo
ks out he would bring them home. But - a lot of them we didn't - I didn't read. The Count of Monte Christo and books like - I've still got some in there - there now that belonged to my father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you remember your mother reading?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. Not very mu
ch - she didn't have a lot of time you know. When I look back and think how she was always at work and I guess she didn't have a lot of time for reading.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You don't remember him reading aloud to her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 There was no reading aloud in that way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
No. Well, there was never - there was never any sort of quiet to listen to reading - especially for my mother you see if she was usually working at the machine and we youngster had to clear the table and wash up and things like that. If my fat
her didn't do it. My father always prepared all the meals.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And you girls would clear away would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes, we all had our share to do - oh yes. And we all did our own mending. The boys used to do the wood chopping - getting the wood and - read
y for the morning, you know, my father used to say now see about the firing for the morning. There was a little bowl you see with little pieces of coal and sticks ready - that all had to be got ready the night before. Oh yes, the boys all had a little job
 to do. And always we had - they - the boys mainly - sometimes we girls had to do our own - we always had to clean our shoes overnight ready for school in the morning. We never went to school with dirty shoes - never allowed to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you remember a funeral in your family when you were a young girl?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
No, I can't remember - the only thing I can remember very much about death was when we lived at the house higher up George Street - the man who I told you was a bootmaker - one of their children died and
 we all had to go in and see this child in a coffin which I thought was dreadful, but we all had to go and see him - whether it was - who - who wanted us to go you see. I don't know whose idea it was - it was evidently the custom of the day you know to se
e people who died - but I don't remember anyone else - ever.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What did you feel about that at the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh, I thought it was awful. Because of course he used to play with us - he was one of our playmates. And - we didn't understand death at all. B
ut - far from keeping it away from us you see they made us go to see this child. Whether it was his mother's wish, but that was rather outstanding in my mind. I don't remember anyone else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Sort of thing that makes an impression on a child.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 It did - yes. Because of course I must have been quite young when I was up there - eight or nine years old perhaps. And that child.....

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You didn't go to the funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. No, can't remember anything about the funeral - I can only remember that this child died and we had to go and see him in his coffin.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You went to see this aunt in Old Marston sometimes did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Mmm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 How often would that be that you'd go there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh quite often - in the summer. In the winter - if we went in the winte
r time - and in those days there were no - no lamps - no pavements up there - it was all a thick rut - muddy - muddy rut. And we had thick boots and the trees that are along there now by St Clements church were very big - I remember always running like an
y
thing along there. 'Cos of course we had to walk everywhere - there were no buses or anything. And coming back from there - if it was dark - we had - we had to run through there - we were very frightened - but in the - in the summer days you see we used t
o walk through the Mesopotamia and up that way. It's lovely through there. And at that time - where there is a bridge across there - there used to be a ferry - a pull ferry. You - you pulled yourself over.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Where is }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1320587\charrsid13250951 Earston}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  ferry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Ah - up the other end - this is in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 Mesopotamia}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  itself - they now have a bridge there. Yes. So we used to walk up that way you see to my aunties.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Was she on your mother's side?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, she was my mothers sister. My mother had a step sister as well and several s
tep brothers - 'cos my grandfather married twice. My mother lost her own mother when she was ten years old. Because - she told us often that when she had the new mother you see, of course my mother had to help look after the babies as they came along but 
-
 she was ten years old and when she was eleven years old - she said that her step mother said to her well now Fanny you're a big girl now you'll have to think of - about going out to work. But - that was eleven. But my sisters - I think - they went out wh
en they were twelve. Well, my mother went into domestic service.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 She did that before she did the machining?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, before she did the machining. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Children didn't have such a long childhood in those days did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You saying that you didn't go out with just your father - you'd go out all together - is that correct?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Generally we went - yes - mother and father and two or three of the children. The older ones were allowed to go out on their own. But they had to be back
 at a certain time you know, my mother - my mother and father would - come - say well now we shall be back and such and such a time - you mind your home by then. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you go out on Bank Holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Where would you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, gen
erally into the fields you see and take - Binsey Lane - the - the farmers fields and places like that you see. There was nowhere else to go - not - much. Or down by the riverside you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you ever go away for a holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. Not when we were children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Can you tell me - on Sundays in those days did your parents think it wrong to work and play on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. We were never allowed to sew a button on}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13250951  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Sundays. And as we got older when we - when we did do those things - we had to go u
pstairs in the bedroom and do it. My father was very particular in that sort of thing. You could read - you could read and - but you were not allowed to sew because you see my three sisters as I say used to make all their own clothes and things and often 
had quite a bit of sewing on hand but not on Sundays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And did you have different clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. You had your best clothes Sundays. Kept for Sunday you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And you used to go to Sunday school - that was St Peter Le Bailey?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did your mother and father go every Sunday to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. Not every Sunday. Well, my mother mainly but not my father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Would he go at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Very seldom. Very seldom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Were there any activities connected with the church - any clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. And we used to go to a - we used to go to a Band of Hope and those sort of things you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you sign the pledge?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 And - my mother always went to the - the Mothers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1320587\charrsid13250951 #}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1320587\charrsid13250951 S}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 wing }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1320587\charrsid13250951 M}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 eeting and that, you know, they had - they called them Mothers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1320587\charrsid13250951 
\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 
 Meetings on a Monday and took her sewing or did other sewing there for sale of work and things like that and - I remember her saying - you see in those days the rector of St Peter Le Bailey was the Reverend Chevasse who later became the Bishop of Li
verpool, well, they had twin sons - my mother had twin daughters - they were much of an age and - one became the Bishop of Rochester didn't he - he came back to St Peter le Bailey or rather to St Peters College and then he became Bishop of Rochester. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 The o
ther one, Noel Chevass, was killed in the first world war - but they would be the same age as my mothers twins - and my mother took her twins to this sewing meeting, you see, and I always remember her telling the story that Mrs Chevasse - she had twin boy
s and she said that although she had a nanny for them she always had them at night because the nanny had had them all day and Mrs Chevasse herself looked after them through the night. I remember my mother telling that story.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What about Sunday school outings - did you have them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes. It used to be a horse with a brake in those days. But mainly we went to Blenheim Palace - for our Sunday school outing. And - we went by train which was wonderful to us. But sometimes we went by brake and they took
 all the bread and butter and buns and things you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Just children who went?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, mainly children - I think many of the parents ever went - they were glad to get rid of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You said that grace was said at meals - who said the grace?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 We all had to - all of us - yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Was it said at all meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. Well - sitting down meals - dinner and tea you see. Breakfast as I say was a run about affair - we - we weren't all there together.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Were you taught to say prayers at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
We - younger children were. I can't remember the older ones - but I - I remember my mother making us kneel down at the bedside - yes, and just saying a little prayer. Sometimes it was just the - ordinary Lords Prayer - but sometimes it was somet
hing different - something we'd learn at school and we used to have the little texts from school you see, which we would read one of those. But of course as we got older we - nothing of that was done - when we started going out to work and things like tha
t you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 But you would have been grouped together for that would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes, oh yes. Well, we generally all went to bed together you see - same time - oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You didn't belong to the choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you know what your father's political views were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
He always voted Conservative so far as I can remember. I don't know much about it in those days really. The time I can remember most was the - the candidate here for Conservatism was Lord Valentia and we used to - as children
 you see we were very naughty - we used to sing - vote, vote, vote for Lord Valentia - turn Tommy Whale out of town. That was the other candidate - he was Liberal. There was only Liberal and Conservatives you see. For Valentia is the man and we'll have hi
m if we can. I remember singing that you know, not knowing what it meant.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You don't know why your father was a Conservative?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. No, I've no idea - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What about your mother - do you know what her views were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, I can't remember - bu
t she - I think like the majority of women in those days - they voted as their husbands voted. I don't think they had much to say in the way of politics you know, looking back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you remember your father voting in a general election before 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Well, he always went to vote whenever there was an election - I can always remember them saying it was their duty to vote and they voted - they went as a duty - oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 At that time in some places men felt that they risked their jobs if they voted differently from their employers or landlord.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, I - they might have done - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you know if that affected your father at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 I don't think so because you see - most of the time that I can remember my father he hadn't got regular work. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And what about your landlord - who was that where you were in .....?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well we - we rented from the corporation - in both the houses - they belonged to the corporation I remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you know if he was a member of the Conservative party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
No, I can never remember him belonging to anything like that. He might have done but I can never remember that. Never remember him going to a club or anything - special club or anything like that - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you remember him doing any work for the Conservatives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 When your parents weren't actually working how did they spend their time - what leisure activities did they have - if any?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well I don't think they had a great deal. My father used to go along to the pub.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Was that quite - how often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
No, no, he - he didn't go - perhaps about once a week you know. No, because, I remember some of the older boys going round to fetch the supper beer - which was a pint of beer for tuppence you see and they had a glass each ou
t of that for their supper. But none of us were ever allowed to taste it. But the older boys they were allowed to go round with the jug in those days - there wasn't bottled stuff and things you see. And it was considered dreadful for a - a younger person 
to be in a pub you see - so that it was only the older ones who were allowed to fetch the supper beer - or perhaps my mother or father would fetch it themselves you know, remember a lot about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 When you say when he got older he drank rather more was that later on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, it was later in - in life - you see when I was grown up more.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you remember your mother going out to enjoy herself at all - any sort of social activities?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes, she - there used to be little - little things connec
ted with the church, you know. Church socials and the sewing meetings, extra tea party or something like that - oh yes, she used to go out - sometimes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Would they go out together or would that just be for women?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, would be just for women, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you remember them going out together in the evening to anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, if they went out together it was generally to visit my aunt you see. The }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3757345\charrsid13250951 A}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 unt Bolter at Marston. No, I can't remember them going out - gallivanting then as we used to
 call it. No, there wasn't the pleasure you see. Mostly - most of your pleasure you made at home you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did your father take part in sport?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, I can't remember him - the boys used to go and play football - but I can't remember my father ever doing anything like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you know if he took an interest in the races and betted and that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh no. No. Never remember him doing that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Were there any other savings clubs you belonged to besides the Capes clothing club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
We saved money at school - the Reverend Sherwood was here and his two sisters - they had a very - they - big house - the house is still there at the bottom of Fisher Row loading through into St Thomas's - and they lived there - the two Miss Sherwoods. We
ll, they came to the school on Monday mornings you see with their cards - collecting cards - and we children - and my mother used to make us little Dorothy bags just to fit the cards and the cards and the money were put in there and we had to hand the car
d
s as they were to Miss Sherwood. She took the money out - we were not allowed to touch the money you see - my mother counted it all in - so much for this card and so much for that you see. So all that we did when we got there - we had to say threepence on
 
Maggie's card and threepence on my card and so on and so on and she counted the money out and that was saved for us each week and then that was given to us at the end of the year. She had a paying out day - generally my mother used to come you see and col
lect all the money. But - if you wished to have it made out to a certain place in the town to spend at a certain shop - she made it out for that shop and it was all signed and then you had a penny in the shilling discount from there. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, they did that you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you make that decision sometimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Yes, sometimes you did. But if you drew the money out - if you wanted the money from Miss Sherwood you had to get notice and then she gave you a penny in the shilling
 for all that you'd - saved. She probably had an interest from the Bank you see for that. But that was a penny in the shilling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And besides that was there anything else for boots or doctors clubs or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, in some Parish's, you see, although we all went to school to St Peter le }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 Bailey}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  we were actually in St Mary }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 Magdalene}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  Parish. And there used to be - something that they gave out at Christmas time like beef and coal for poor families. And - there used to be so many overcoats for old men
 and - so many bags of coal or so much beef - five shillings worth of beef perhaps or five shillings or ten shillings worth of groceries - something like that - distributed round the various poorer families - like big families - people with big families. 
A
nd I remember my father - he had an overcoat offered to him. It was through some charity no doubt you see and he refused it because he never wore an overcoat all his life - he never wore an overcoat and I think - by some reasoning and that - when it was a
l
l explained we had the equivalent - I think the coat - overcoats were valued at two pound and they were made by a tailor at the top of George Street where Perrings are now and I think we must have had the equivalent in groceries or something, one year. Bu
t
 I don't remember us having it very often - everybody didn't - the same people didn't have it every year you see - they were chosen each year. And I think it must have been - I don't know for sure - but I think it must have been you know for the size of t
he family and - your conditions of whatever you got.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you remember your parents getting help from the Guardians?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. No. No. Because we lived quite close to the place - the Parish Relief as they called it in those days - Mr Butler used to run i
t at the bottom of Gloucester Green. We used to play with their grandchildren. But - no, I never remember my mother ever going to the Parish - they called it Parish Relief in those days. No, I don't think we were quite so poor as that you know we all - we
 managed. Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 When you were playing - you played round Gloucester Green - would you play with your brothers and sisters or with other children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 With the - the boys and girls. The boys and girls used to play more together then than what they 
do now. It wasn't all girls together and all boys together. We used to play with the boys - we used to be just as noisy as the boys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And your brothers and sisters too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. Yes, always the older brothers and sisters there to take care of the 
younger ones you see. The younger ones were never allowed out - I was never allowed out there by myself. And the two younger boys - and as we grew up, see, I had to look after the two younger boys - they were never on their own, nobody was ever on their o
wn - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you ever play in other children's houses or yards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Very seldom. Well, in - I did used to play in one peoples yard - across the way - across the road there was a public house and the father had a rag and bone store at the back - a she
d place at the back and stable - he used to let out part for stabling. Sometimes for the bargees horses you know they used to come up - the horses used to draw the barges in those days when they delivered the coal and then they would stable their horses a
t this place and they had a big rough yard with a nice big loft up above, you know. We used to think that was wonderful. It's about the only place I can remember going to. Other peoples houses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What about in your own yard - did you play there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 We
ll, there was no room - for playing. It was quite a small yard at the back. And we wanted all that for my mother's mangle and - lines for doing the washing and that, you know. Nowhere much to play at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Were you allowed to get dirty when you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. But you had to clean yourself up afterwards you know, before you went indoors.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Where would you do that then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Out at the tap at the back if you were in your own yard you see - if not you shot through very quickly, pretending you we
re going up to the lavatory you see, and by the time you came back and came in you'd had a good wash.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you remember what games you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, I can remember one that we used to play and it was called I-okey. And that was, you - you went roun
d and hid somewhere you see, called I-okey and the others had to find you. And another one I remember - jumping - one boy would stand against the wall like that you see and bend down, and the others all had to jump up on top of him and then join on so tha
t you had quite a long serpent and you had to try and jump up all these, but we girls used to be just as bad as the boys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Sort of like leap-frog you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. Yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Were you free to play with anyone you pleased?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. Used to
 play marbles quite a bit. And - another - another thing we used to play was - we used to have books like this - small books you see, and we used to stick pins in there - but inside we used to cut up another newspaper - any picture or any picture out of a
n
 old book and tuck it all in there you see, and then we used to say a pin for a dip - and if they gave you a pin which you stuck in the back there - they could have a dip, you see. And they dipped their pin in like that and whatever picture was in there t
hey had it. A pin a dip we used to call it - that was one of our favourite games.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did your parents ever play with you outside or in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh no, I can't remember them ever doing that. Playing with us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you have any board games like ludo?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, oh yes. Ludo, snakes and ladders and all those sort of games.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 But they didn't play them with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes. They did those indoors - oh yes. And - we used to play happy families with cards and things like that - but not the ordinary card ga
mes, you know. Not the gambling card games - you were never allowed to play with those. The - happy families and snap and things like that we were allowed to play. But my mother and father used to play ludo with us. Quite a few of those sort of games we h
ad you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 They didn't discourage you from playing with certain children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh no. Oh no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you go to any theatres - this theatre where your brothers worked at - was that where the new theatre is?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. And I remember my first pantomime there. And it was called Sinbad the Sailor - I thought it was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 marvellous}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
 of course. But how I came to go there was - my three sisters that worked at Lucas's factory - Mr Lucas was one of the directors of the theatre and one of his treats at Christmas
 was to give all the employees a free ticket for the pantomime. And - if, sometimes my sisters didn't want to use their own - they were perhaps going to a dance or something like that you see - they gave the ticket to my mother - two tickets - sometimes t
hree - to take the children - I was one of the children. And my - I remember going with my mother - on these free tickets to the pantomime and it was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 Sinbad}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  the Sailor. Beautiful I thought it was, you know. And then sometimes of course my - brothers would h
ave complementary tickets. And if they didn't want them for their girl friends well then mother had them. That's how we came to go to the theatre - we could never afford to pay very much you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you remember going to a cinema at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Concerts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
No. I - I - we used to go to concerts in the town hall but they were mainly school concerts and things like that. But the first sort of entertainment that I can remember going to where you paid - it was only tuppence - was a bioscope in t
hose days - the forerunner of the cinema. Called Our Navy - in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3757345\charrsid13250951 C}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 orn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3757345\charrsid13250951 E}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 xchange in Oxford in George Street - and of course that was a wonderful thing for us. And then of course we saw the bioscopes and things in }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 Glouc}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  - in St Giles fair - very primitive o
f course but - that was the only sort of forms of entertainment bar the theatre which of course to us was a fairy land - the theatre.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 St Giles fair - was that quite an event in Oxford?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes, you always saved up for the fair. You put your money
 in your money box you see. Then my father opened it when it was fair time. And - we had so much to spend on - each day - out of your own money. We saved one and six - two shillings perhaps. And of course you were very rich if you had a shilling each day 
to spend. But you always saved up for the fair - then your box was sealed down again and you saved up for Christmas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Were you ever given any money or was it all earned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, we mainly earned. We might have had perhaps a penny. We might have had 
an extra penny for doing the knives and forks and things like that you know, if we'd been especially good.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 It wouldn't be regular then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh no. My mother used to buy a pound of boiled sweets every Saturday night at Gibbs in the covered market fo
r fourpence. And we all had a little screw of those on Sunday mornings. Sitting up in bed generally - and my mother would come up with all these little screws of paper - we all had a little - pennyworth of sweets you know. And they were all shared out exa
ctly - for everybody. It's a pound - a whole pound you see, was taken. Perhaps - we would have it twice - once on Sunday morning and once in the week but everybody had exactly the same number of sweets. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did any relations or neighbours ever come in and give your mother a hand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, not neighbours. And we only had this one auntie. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 The one in Marston?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. That - you know, wasn't very near. She wasn't very near and she was older than my mother too, so that - probably some of
 the neighbours came in - and gave a hand but you see we were a big family and - the older ones always turned to and helped. Helped with the younger ones - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you remember when your mother had your two younger brothers how she managed then? I think you mentioned somebody who came in then?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Yes, there was a Mrs Kitchen. More or less, you know, the old midwife that used to come round. But she only came in just to attend to my mother. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 At the birth you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. And my father 
- he did the cooking and all that sort of thing you see, and cleaning and the older girls - we just - we just managed, you know. Nobody came in - and definitely no one to pay because - in those days there weren't the helps - anyone who came in to help - a
t all, wouldn't be expected to pay. Probably a neighbour would come in and take the nappies away and things like that you know but they wouldn't expect any payment - it was just done as neighbourliness you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 But in your case a neighbour wouldn't have done that because of the older girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
No, because of the older children, you see. The - the woman might have taken the nappies but otherwise - everything else was done at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Besides this aunt there was no other relative living nearby in Oxford?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
No. There were - my mother had a step-sister. But she also had her family and that, you see, and her husband - he was on the sea and she was more or less away from Oxford - at Portsmouth - they had rooms at Portsmouth you see when he was away at sea.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did your parents have friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes. My mother had quite a few - women friends, you know, that she used to go to mothers meetings and things with - there was - there was very little else. And I remember the name of that clergyman that they all fell in love with - the Reverend }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 McNab}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 . And - she used to go to his - I think it was Monday evening - meeting - special meetings at church you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And she'd go with her friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes, always with a friend - a Mrs Potter - she used to 
be quite friendly with and she again had a big family you see. We children were left - sometimes the Potters children would come to us and sometimes we would go up there, we younger ones. The older ones of course had their own interests and went off out o
n their own.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 So how old would you be when you'd be left without an older person to look after you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh, we weren't left without someone - ever.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 So if you went over to the Potters there would be an older person?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 There would be an older 
Potter there - yes. It might be their turn to look after the children you see or while the mothers went out. Well, mothers didn't go out very much you know. No, they didn't have the freedom that they do nowadays. And of course there weren't the places to 
g
o to. Because although we were near to the theatre and my brothers worked there it was only a pantomime times that we ever went - we younger ones you see - and my mother took us. She used to go occasionally on a complimentary ticket to other things but th
en she went - well, either with one of the older girls or a friend you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 This Mrs Potter did she ever come into the house for a meal or tea or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, very seldom. There was never very much of that sort of entertaining - no. Yo
u only entertained on special days - birthdays and things like that you know. Although of course - there was always the comradeship of - if they came in round - round about tea time there was always a cup of tea or something like that - but no preparation
s or no special invitations. I can't remember at least.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did neighbours drop in then sometimes unannounced?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Not very often. No, I don't think - well, perhaps my mother was one of those people who didn't encourage it. Of people dropping in on - any
 old time like some people were in the habit - and still are now of course. She was never one of those sort of people to - just go and have a gossip with somebody. She hadn't time for one thing. No, she hadn'd time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did your father have friends of his own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Very few I imagine, unless it was just the people that he met in the public house. There was one man used to come that he - he used to go to these sale rooms - furniture sales and things with you know. And - well I guess that he met him on the 
- furniture removing business and they had that interest of - buying old things - or rather acquiring them cheaply I expect it was, you see, being in that line of business - I guess they had the opportunity to buy things. We had one or two quite nice piec
es which would be considered antiques now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did they have friends in common - a couple that they would be friendly with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, I can't - I can't remember anyone like that - not that - not another married couple you mean don't you. No, no I don't rem
ember. We - more or less brought up on our own - we always had plenty of friends to go about with and play with and that you know, but no one sort of very intimate that was - not - they weren't encouraged at least to run in and out the house - we weren't.
 We could always take friends home but - we can't say that we were encouraged to just bring anybody in you know. But my mother and father always wanted to know where we'd been and who we'd been with. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And if you had a young man would they expect to meet him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes, yes. But - well, in those days - I mean - you see nowadays you see boys and girls fourteen and fifteen going out together - well, we didn't do that in those days at that age we were still playmates then, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 In a crowd you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Yes, go round together. And when the fair came of course that - the St Giles fair was one of our highlights, you see, and we used to make up a little party and all go round together. And we all stayed together. There was no going off in p
airs like nowadays.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What age then did you start going off in pairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, I didn't go out with a boyfriend until I was about seventeen. Then I put my hair up. Used to have it down in a plait until then.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Was it your decision to put it up or was it your mothers idea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
No, it - why I put mine up - we'd - most of us usually had it put up - we used to have a big black bow here and one at the bottom you see and then where I was working my boss acquired a new place - he had it built - which i
s now Ferrings at the top - the furniture shop at the top of George Street - and that was a - a beautiful new building and he always told us he was very proud because he hadn't got a monkey on the top and I never knew what that meant. But it meant a mortg
a
ge. I didn't know but I - I used to wonder why - I used to look up for the monkey. He was very proud to tell people - it was all his he hadn't got a monkey on the top. And when I went up there I was promoted then you see to the front shop and I put up my 
hair. In }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3757345\charrsid13250951 M}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 erry }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3757345\charrsid13250951 W}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 idow curls which was fashionable at that time. The }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3757345\charrsid13250951 M}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 erry }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3757345\charrsid13250951 W}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
idow was a play you see - a musical play in London - and the - it was the fashion then was called the merry widow curls so I put up my hair at seventeen. Then I required a boyfriend I suppose or several at least. Oh yes I was quite grown up then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Can you tell me how you remember the different social classes round where you were or in Oxford generally at the time when you were a girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, yes, because - we were the ordinary
 working class people you see and then there were the better class people of what we called North Oxford - Banbury Road - Woodstock Road - mere college people - you see, they were considered the better class people. And a lot of the girls of my age and yo
u
nger went into domestic service to these people - those houses you see. But they were considered all the better class people living up that way. And - then there were some people which I suppose - if we'd been snobbish - which we were not allowed to be - 
w
ere poorer than us, you see. Quite poor and hadn't got half the things we had - not half so well off as we were. That would be - well I suppose you'd call them the poorer classes - in those days people did. Nowadays they don't - I mean there's no - there'
s not so much class distinction. There was a certain class distinction here Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 In the working class itself there was a distinction?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Not exactly - there was a division you see between those and the people you worked for - they were always c
onsidered better class you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Can you remember being taught to treat the people in what you call the better class differently from other people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, not to be - not to be sort of humble.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Not like in the villages?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, oh no. Where my
 husband was brought up out at Waterstocks he - when he went to live with those old aunts - there was always the squire of the village there and he had to doff his hat and the girls had to curtsey. 'Course the squire owned everything. But not in Oxford. W
e
 were brought up - we were brought up - we were taught to be respectful and to speak properly to people but we never felt that we were any different to the ordinary everyday person - but the other people were better class - better off than us you see. And
 of course when I went into shop we always had to say yes Madam and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 no Madam}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  - Sir. It just came natural to us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You'd been brought up to do it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. We'd all been brought up to respect older people you see - oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you remember anyone calling your mother Madam or your father Sir?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh no. No. No, we were just ordinary working folk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 In the district round where you were do you know if there were any people who were considered important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, no - because you see we lived
 in George Street and there were very few private houses - it was all shops and that round about you see. I should think there were only about a dozen private houses all told in George Street at that time. There were various shops and as I tell you about 
thirteen public houses and things you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
The actual shopkeepers who owned these shops - who did they associate with - who was their sort of circle of friends and that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, they sort of wouldn't associate with my father - not - I
 mean they might meet him perhaps out - there was one - one man - Doctor Galpin - he was the solicitor - he was the City Corner actually and the solicitor and he was one of these hale fellow well met sort of people and he always walked down the street wit
h
 his hand on my husbands - my fathers shoulder. It - but he was one of those men - everybody was equal to him you see - I mean although my father would perhaps come down the street with a carpenters apron on. But Mr Galpin - he was always a friend to ever
y
body and he would walk down the street with my father the same as he would perhaps with a fellow solicitor you see. But he was always - I - I've heard him many times say 'hello Henry my boy' and just walk down the street with him - although my father was 
just a carpenter or a - a man - an ordinary working man you see. Oh no, there was - I don't think there was a lot of class prejudice. You just - knew that you were not quite so good as those people - as far as position went you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Can you remember if there was a non-conformist chapel round there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
There was a chapel - there was a chapel where the cinema is built and my boss was married there. It was a Congregational church and we used to go to the Band of Hope in the schoolroom round the back, yo
u see, which was in Gloucester Green. But it was a Congregational church and my boss was a member of it and - he was married there and he was very upset when it - they sold it to be put into a cinema and he - he left it before it was pulled down I think. 
H
e was so upset that it was going to be sold that he went - he joined the Baptist chapel then on top of New Road. Oh yes, there was the Congregational church and there was another church down below by the fire station which was built - my father and mother
 told me - as a church of ease for the St Mary }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 Magdalene}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
 church because it became so full and they had to have one to take the overflow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you remember what sort of people went to chapel?-
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, yes, the - well, the ordinary folk like us and a lot of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 
trades people}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 . I remember seeing Mr Webber married there. Webbers in High Street - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Talking about what you said if you'd been allowed to be snobbish - do you remember a distinction being made between the rough and respectable working class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. You used to get the rough people as well you know, and we were told of course not to mix with those people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 When people said they were rough what exactly did they mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well they used to think that they were badly brought up an
d dirty you see. Don't mind with those sort of people - they're not your class sort of thing - although my mother and father always impressed on us that - when you go out hold your head up high - you're equally as good as anyone else. Without being snobbi
sh, but you'd nothing to hide if you conduct yourselves in a proper manner. That was always impressed on us you see - to conduct ourselves in a proper manner and then no one could sort of pick on us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Would you say that they themselves had the same attitude to people in other classes?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh no, not everybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What I meant was your parents had this attitude - were they the same?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh - oh yes. They used - yes, they used to go out holding up their head with - well, my father used to say we don
't owe anyone anything so therefore we can walk about with a free head. High head. Oh yes, perhaps - perhaps it was a little bit snobbish in their way you know, but it was their - their way. I think my father must have come from a very good family - we - 
h
e had only one brother - no sisters - that we ever knew, you see. But - I think he had very good connections. Because he used to speak of - some relations of his who had a shop in the High Street. Well, of course, if you had a shop in the High Street in t
hose days you were of good standing. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And of course that book that you gave too that was on his family wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 No, that was my husband's people - side - that was that side. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes, and - and - you know we've heard my father speak of yo
u know various people and - as I tell you he didn't have a lot of schooling. There weren't the schools you see but - where he did go they had to pay sixpence a week which I suppose was quite a - a little sum.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 A lot of his generation were illiterate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
They had no schooling at all - as you see by that writing of his with those names. He wrote beautifully and he had a wonderful memory. He could remember all sorts of things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you remember anyone at that time being described as a real gentleman or a real lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Well, we had the people that lived up North Oxford mainly professors and things you see. And, as I said, Lord Valentia put up for parliament and there were those sort of people. But out the other way you see - Banbury way - the - the - Lord \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 - I see his house has just been broken into hasn't it. Cut here and a lot of the property round there - those were - and Valentias you see, they were at - Harcourt.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you remember people using the term though irrespective of their being a member of the aristocracy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes, there were some very nice ladies about - different people who - they became Justice of the Peace and things - well-known in Oxford - oh yes, there were quite a few a - a - nice people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you remember people moving from one class to another either up or down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Marrying into - a higher? No, I don't think so. I don't think I can remember anything of that - not anyone sort of very special you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Your home was rented from the corporation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. I suppose in those days it was - six or seven shillings a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You never saw anything of the landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, it was all done through an agent you see, my mother had to pay the rent at the office you see. Tilby and Co. It was then on Sarfax -
 'course it's all done now through the City Treasurers office but - of course it was - Oxford wasn't such a big place then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Were you given lessons by either of your parents at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 How old were you when you first went to school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Five. But some of the younger ones went at three. They - they used to take children of three but we three younger ones didn't go until we were five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 When you first started did you go for the whole day or part of the day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 The whole day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And come home for dinner or have it at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh, come home always. There was nothing at school in those days. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You were near enough to come home weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. Oh yes. And we had to wait until the older ones cam
e to fetch us from the infants - we were in the infant school you see - and we had to wait until some of the older ones came to fetch us home - we were not allowed to come through on our own. Although it wasn't very far away. You see, St Peters - where St
 Peters hall is - and only round to George Street but - we always had to have an escort.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Was the infants a separate building from the elementary school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes - no, underneath. The infant school was - underneath and the big school, as we called it,
 up top. And boys and girls together - mixed. No separation. No. When I first went to school you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Right up until you left?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 It was a church school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You used to walk to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 How long did it take you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, about ten minutes I suppose you see. Be round there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did the older ones take you to school too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes, when we went back we all went }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 back together}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And in the morning did you go on your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, we were alw
ays taken. The older ones always took us younger ones. We all got ready for school together you see - the boys were allowed to go off on their own but the girls - and the two younger boys - and me you see all had to be taken.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What did you think of school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Well I liked it. When I went I was always quite keen to go. I don't know what my brothers thought about it. But - I - I've destroyed all my old school photographs. When - you know the photographers used to come round taking photographs - well, o
f course our mothers couldn't afford to have a photograph of everybody - if you'd got say five or six children as we had - there was twins, three, four - about six of us you see going to school together. My oldest sister and myself - oh and the twins too 
-
 and then my two younger brothers. Well, it was always - possible for the older ones to come down to have their photographs taken with the younger ones to come down to have their photographs taken with the younger ones so that you were all on the one phot
ograph because your parents couldn't afford to buy a separate photograph of everybody. So mainly we were three or four of us together in the photograph you see. Sometimes they couldn't all get in together but - that's how they used to do it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 How did you feel about the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh well, we went to school to be taught and we respected the teachers and that was it and - oh, we had some very nice teachers of course like all children - oh I don't like Miss so and so but everybody says that don't they
. We had some very nice people really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Can you remember what the teachers emphasized as particularly important in your general behaviour and life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, I think the main were the three R's you know always and we were taught to write and we were 
taught to pronounce the - the words properly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 They thought it was important the way you spoke did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes, oh yes. You see it was written on the blackboard and it was divided too and you pronounced the - the two halves and then you put it together and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
And when you were speaking to the teachers - if they asked you a question - say as you got older, when you'd learnt to read and write - would they be careful about your }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 pronunciation}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. You would - you would - he brought - if
 you were quite good at something you know, you would be brought out to the front and you would read it to the teacher and she would make any corrections you see and tell you if you were not doing it - and then you would be complimented if you'd done it n
icely, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you remember if they emphasized manners or tidiness or punctuality?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes. Punctuality especially. And - if you'd come to school punctually the whole of the term - you had so many extra marks you see for that. Your books -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you get }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 attendance}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  prizes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Yes. Yes, you did. You had prizes for - in those days they didn't call it Religious Instruction as they do now a days - it was just called the scripture lesson you see and we had prizes for scripture lesson. I had pri
zes for dictation. I - I had prizes for dictation and my sister - she had prizes for spelling - special spelling - yes - oh we - I think - take us on the whole we - we took a - home our quota of prizes. It was always a prize giving at the end the year you
 see - special prizes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 We used to have books -What Katy Did at School was one of my prize ones.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 If you did something the teachers didn't like what would they do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh well, you were brought out in the front you see. In disgrace. And if you were .....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Would you be stood in the corner then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes, you would stand for so long with your hands behind your back and your back to the class - you were really in disgrace.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Would you be kept behind after school or caned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Very little - kee
ping in after school. You might have been kept in after school to do some lines - not many you know - but you didn't - they didn't send you home to do them. And if you were really naughty and - cheeky to the teacher - if she couldn't cope with it herself 
or himself, whichever it was - you were sent along to the headmaster you see and then you had a cane.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you ever have that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. Oh very often because you see we used to have the cane - we were naughty of course and then when we went home and c
omplained about it you see our parents said 'oh well, expect you deserved it' - that was all he said.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Was the cane used a great deal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes, on some of the boys. I remember one boy taking off his boot - throwing it at the master and one boy th
rew a slate - we - we used to have the slates you know and - then of course he - he had to come out and he had a proper whacking I suppose. But it wasn't always done in front of the others. Probably away .....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Would the teachers themselves cane or was it just the head?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes, the teacher could cane you - oh yes. They could correct you. Yes, you had one or two stripes whatever it was on your hand. Or you might have had just the ruler you see, they would come round - if you were misbehaving in the
 desks the teacher would come round the back of you - if you were drawing or sticking stuff in the ink pots, you know, what we used to do, put the blotting paper in the ink pot. You see you'd have just a - a knock on your knuckles with the - with the rule
r - nothing very hard of course. I suppose we thought it was awful in those days - but it was nothing to hurt anyone - but it was a correction. And we took it as such.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did your parents show an interest in your school work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. Oh yes, we alwa
ys - we had our copy books to take home you see. And - we had to copy the - the proper writing you know - thin going up and hard coming down and so on. Oh yes, and my father well, he was interested in all that sort of thing you see and made us do the thin
g and they certainly did compliment us if we needed it you see. Oh yes, they encouraged us in that way. In every way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you remember them visiting the school or meeting the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes, they used to come up on prise giving day. You see. I c
an't remember my father coming very much. But my mother used to come because - you see, she used to meet these different people at the - not at the sewing meetings - but at things connected with those - they used to have little meetings of other sorts and
 all the school people and church people you see used to come.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 So she'd meet the teachers through those things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. She'd know them anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 At that school did the other children come from similar types of home to yours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, mainly - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Were there some that didn't?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
There were some little rougher than us but - and there's some a little better, perhaps, you see, their people were perhaps in a better position than my father or mother was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you remember the teachers singling out some children for different treatment from others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
No. No, I can't remember anything of that. I think it was all pretty - pretty much the same. There was never any - there was never any children saying - ah teachers pet - like you do her
e you know. There seemed to be nothing of that much in my day - not that I can remember. It was all very placed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 There weren't any work house children there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 No, there was a - there were one or two children that came from a children's home - opp
osite the school was a house - it's still there - and there were two sisters sister Alice and sister Ellen - they may not have been sisters you see that was their title really. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 It was a }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 children's}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  home for - probably orphans you see, and they were looked a
fter in this home - perhaps there were about a dozen and they had to attend the school you see, because it was a Parish school. And I remember these children being taken out all in a crocodile with these two old sisters you see. They were evidently childr
en with no parents.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 How did they get on at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh, exactly the same as we - they - they were not treated any differently at all. They were not looked down upon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And they weren't left out of things by the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh no. No, they were simply - I do remember we sort of looked upon them as the home children. But - nothing more than that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Not a stigma?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh no, not in any way. It was simply that they were called the home children because they came from the home, you see, we k
new nothing different.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Were there any cliques or groups or gangs in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, no, I can't - I can't remember that they - we all seemed to be school kids together you know and - play together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 How old were you when you left?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Th
irteen. I went to work on my thirteenth birthday. I left school on what they called a labour certificate. And that was - if you were proficient - you see, I was in the highest class then by a - by the time I was thirteen, and - could sort of get no higher
 
- except to be a sort of monitor - unless I was going in for pupil teaching and then I would be more or less given a little training as a pupil teacher - that was different to the training - that was the only training there was at - in those days. No, if 
m
y mother could prove that I had a job to go to - she could fill in a form by which I could be given a labour certificate to leave school at thirteen. Otherwise you stayed on you see 'til you were fourteen or - between then and - getting a job. But you - t
here were no children running about the streets between school and jobs you understand me. Well, I got the job myself actually. We lived opposite this shop - Delamars and there was a notice put in the window.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You saw an advertisement for this job - was it in a local paper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
No, it was in the window of the shop and I went over and applied for it you see and my mother came over as well and they said I could start.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 If you could have stayed at school longer would you have liked to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, I suppose I'd got as far as I could. Well, I suppose I had you see then. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 There was nothing to specialize in those days. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You see. And - I could have stayed on as a pupil teacher probably but - this job came along and there you are.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 The money you'd earned before you had your job had been in the errands?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes, just the errands.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You'd not had any other part time work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Can you tell me a little bit about the job - what exactly had you to do and what your hours were and that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Well, we worked from half past eight in the morning 'til eight o'clock at night. We had an hour off for lunch - half an hour off for tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Afternoon tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you have a morning break?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, no morning - oh dear, 
no. You - you went right through 'til lunch time and then you went home you see. Any of the people that were working there that had come from a distance used to bring their sandwiches and things. And - make - they could make a cup of tea there - they had 
t
o buy everything themselves you see. But what they did in those days you see - they got a pint of milk and everybody shared it - then the next day somebody else - it was their turn - we took it in a rote of that you see. But usually you took your own litt
le bit of tea and little bit of sugar and all put in the pot together you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you have a half day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Not until I'd been working there some time. And then that came into force and we closed at four o'clock on Thursday afternoon and then it became absolute law that you closed at one o'clock you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Were you still working there when you closed at one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. Yes. We closed at one o'clock but we had to clear all up so that it was half past before we got out really. But we did have the ha
lf day on Thursday then. That all came into force while I was working.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you work Saturdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Full day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. And then the various laws came in you know where we closed a little earlier instead of working on 'til eight o'clock we
 closed at seven. But it was never less than seven when I was working - all the time. And then on St Giles }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3757345\charrsid13250951 F}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 air }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3757345\charrsid13250951 Night}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
 - see that was one of our very busiest nights - one half of us went off at six o'clock one night and worked right through 'til eleven o'cl
ock the next night. Because the fair used to be on at eleven and it being a - a toy shop you see - 'course you've always got somebody coming at five to eleven. And we used to supply you see - we used - we were wholesalers too - we used to supply the - fai
r people with lots of goods. I've counted up thousands of pounds worth of copiers. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 
We used to take their money that they took on the roundabouts and things - they used to come and buy their stuff with it you see, the next day.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You said the shop was in High Bridge Street didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Ah - only at latter years. This was in George Street, you see, opposite where I lived. Right opposite where I lived. And then they went up to the top shop. Well, he bought that new place then - after I left - oh many, m
any years after. That was sold and he had the other place and just as a wholesale business - not you see, when we went off to the top shop we were - we had our wholesale trade where we supplied all these smaller shops and we also had a retail trade sellin
g sweets in one shop - sweets and biscuits in one shop and toys in the other. And therefore you see when we had St Giles fair we used to do a big trade then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And you used to serve?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. Used to serve and help with the books.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did they teach you how to do that or had you learnt it at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Well, you just learned at you went along. You see, book-keeping - when you were not serving you had to fill in the time doing something. And one of my - one of my jobs was to - you see we used to have - out rides we called them - the commercial }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 travellers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
 that used to go out to the shops and take the orders - well when they came back one of my jobs was to count up his money - take all the accounts and then do all his booking - the orders that he'd take
n - put into a book ready to go out into the warehouse for them to make up the orders. And it used to do quite a lot of writing then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Would you have liked another job or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 Well, I did ask once - my sister was at the Kad}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3757345\charrsid13250951 ima}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951  - I think I told y
ou - and they wanted waitresses there - she then was a supervisor and - she suggested that perhaps I might like to go there but it never materialized - I didn't - I used to think I would like to go you know. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And - then - my mother said well why don't you ask Mr Delamare for a rise instead. It was going to be two shillings more I think that I was going to get at the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 Kadima}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  had I gone as a waitress. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 
But - my mother said you know, don't bother - if Mr Delamare gives you another two shillings I should stay on there. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And he did - yes. So - and mother knew.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What were you getting then when you asked him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh only about twelve shillings a week I think. Ten or - I think I was getting ten and he raised me to twelve. I was only getting about sixteen when I le
ft after staying there thirteen years, see, you had to ask for rises in those days - you didn't get automatic rises. As you ages, you know. And you just had your rise on your merit - if he thought you were worth another shilling a week - he'd give it to y
ou but otherwise you didn't get it you see - oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you leave on your marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And you didn't carry on working after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 How did you get on with the other people who worked there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh very well. We were al
l - it was a very friendly atmosphere. Quite an - quite good people to work with. All people like ourselves you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 How did your employer treat you on the whole?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh very well, but - he didn't give anything away - but he gave us good training I 
must say. We had a good training. I didn't leave there because as I say we were quite content there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Have you not done any other work since then - paid work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Only once when my husband was very ill and we were rather on the rocks and I took up a 
job - just a weekend job - Fridays and Saturdays - serving in a cake shop. At Cooper and Boffins. And - for that I had five shillings a day. That was ten shillings for the two days. I went about nine o'clock in the morning until about five o'clock. My hus
band was very poorly for quite a long while - I suppose I was there - oh, perhaps a couple of years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Was that after the end of the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, oh yes. It just helped to tide us over you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you ever belong to a trade union or any organisation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
No, they hadn't - it was 1916 when I left you see to be married and - there - there was nothing of that sort for shop people - there were trade unions of course because my husband belonged to one. But he was apprenticed - I came across his }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 indentures}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
 too the other day - half a crown a week to start with in the - and they - they apprenticed them you see for seven years in those days. You were tied for seven years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And you had four shillings I think when you started?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Four shillings to start with.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And how much went to your mother?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Three. I had to give my mother three shillings and I had sixpence for my pocket money to spend as I liked and sixpence to put on my card for my clothing and shoes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 At Capes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Y
es. And then sometimes you see I would still take a few things for Miss Gardner if I could in the various - perhaps in my lunch hour or something like that. So I still used to get threepence and sixpence then when I - when I was still thirteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you remember feeling that employees and employers had different interests at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, yes, we all had our won - we all had our own little interests you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 I mean a division of interest - a conflict?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, I think there was - no. Reall
y life was much - easier and more placid than it is today. Wasn't so hectic you know. No, life was more reasonable.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you remember feeling there was a division between those who were trained for a craft - had been an apprentice and those who hadn't b
een?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
No, no, I don't think so. We all felt we were - on an equal, you know, with each other. I never wanted to go to - I - I used to say you see - before I left school I used to say 'I don't want to go to the factory'. I never wanted to go into the d
ressmaking work. Although I mean I've seen quite a lot since but I never sort of wanted to go in with all that - the noise because I'd been over there sometimes to - from - with messages for my sisters and that or to fetch them home or things like that yo
u
 know and I used to think what a noisy place it was. I never want - I - that was one of the things I used to say to my mother - oh I don't want to go to the factory. But I - I don't think I was ever keen to go into domestic service and when this job came 
along I - I suppose I must have said something like oh I wouldn't mind doing that. I can sort of picture myself you know. And that\rquote s how I came to go in a shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you think that work changed your }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 attitude}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  to life in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What about your relationship with your mother and father - did that continue the same or did it alter in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes, no, well of course I suppose we felt we were grown up and we went to work and - we also felt - well we are contributing a little, be
cause there - there was very little money about you see, and I suppose at the bottom of us we felt that well, when we go out to work perhaps mother won't have to work so hard. Which she didn't you see with everyone earning and then of course as everyone w
as gradually earning and contributing to the home, and then of course they gradually left and mother was left again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did it make any difference in your relationship with your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, then, you see, they married and went away. 
First of all came the - the war you see that took two of them - one was already married and in the Army. And then the other two went to the war and then I suppose that when they came back they sort of settled down and - and married. They came back to thei
r
 own jobs again - those two. And of course then there were the younger ones and then came the second world war when they were all going. Which disrupted everything. That was - that - that made a big difference to everybody. And all the homes. And in - and
 
in the case of our home you see the - the boys were married and they went to the war - that made no difference to our home - my sister - she - she went to the war - she was nursing. She was in St John Ambulance to start with you see and then she got her e
xperience in the war and then - one of the twins went to - on munitions in London. We others stayed here and of course eventually we all married and left home. 'Til finally there was only my mother and father left.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you spend Sunday any differently when you started to work - I think you told me you continued with Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Yes, we went to Sunday school but then as we got older - we came away from Sunday school but we did attend church. We used to go out walking in the afternoon with our f
riends and that you see. But we mainly went to church at night. Yes. I used to go to then - to the St Mary }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 Magdalene}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
 church - the one opposite Elliston.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Why did you decide to go there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, because some friends of mine went. These two girls tha
t lived across the road at the public house - they went there so we went but I think - I think our main attraction was that where they used to sit just here we could see the organist and we used to be fascinated with this organ you see. And it was Mr Toph
o
use - you know, Tophouse the musical people - his father - well, it would be this one's grandfather of course. And we used to be fascinated with - seeing - watching him playing the organ because we used to sit close by that. And also what fascinated us - 
t
here was a Miss Corbett - she lived in George Street - they had a little sweet shop and sold fishing tackle and things like that. And - she used to clean the church and be the bell ringer and she used to do the calling bell, you know, the five minute to s
even bell - the calling bell, and - and we used to see her doing this bell and I think that fascinated us - I think that's what took us to church. Wicked weren't we.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you make any new friends at this time when you were at work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. Oh yes.
 I - I made one very nice friend and she lived just here - funny thing I should come to live here. In Chapel Street. But she had to walk - she had to walk all the way from here down to work every day. And home for lunch. No buses or anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Where did you meet her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, she used to come home with me for tea sometimes and I used to come up with her. She was very nice girl.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And you hadn't known her at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. No. She was ....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 How did you become acquainted with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 At work. She worked at the same place. Yes, same place, same place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And did you bring her home ever?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes, she used to come in - as I say - you sort of took it in turns in these days to ask a friend to tea on Sunday and then I would come up to her 
house with her on Sunday and we would go walks - down the riverside mainly - our walks used to be along the tow-path you see. And over - to Iffley - from Polly Bridge to Iffley - it was a nice walk then. And then - when she came to us for tea we would go 
the other way up Port Meadow way you see - walk up that way. But usually the side of the river - oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 If you went out either with a girl friend or a boyfriend did you have to be home by a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. Certain time - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What was it - do you remember roughly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Well, about half past nine - we were never out - I - mean when I was seventeen and eighteen it was usually nine or half past nine. Not very much later. Unless I was going with my older sisters - I was allowed to go to d
ances with them you see, and then of course it was when the dance was finished - which was usually ten o'clock. But about half past ten was about the latest we were ever allowed out.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Even at a dance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. Unless it was - occasionally they had what they called a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 Cinderella}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  dance - that was twelve o'clock. But then of course by that time we used to have an escort., to bring us home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You mean somebody would take you - a boyfriend?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 A boyfriend would bring you home you see. Never allowed t
o come home on your own from dances. Oh no, they were very gallant in these days you see, always used to see the girls home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Would they fetch you from your home to take you to the dance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 I think you said you met your husband at a dance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Yes, actually, my sister - one of my twin sisters and her friends - they were very good dancers indeed and - they offered to teach some of those boys from the University Press, you see, at their club in Walton Street and they had - the
y had a teachers Mr. Webb - the music - dance teacher - Mr Webb and Mr Aldridge, K.C's and they used to teach dancing - properly teach it, you see you did it step by step. Well, there were several of these boy apprentices wanted to come and learn to dance
 
and there were some of the girls that were good dancers - like my sisters and Miss Bolton and several more - and they offered to go and teach these boys - take them on as pupils you see. All done for nothing - it was all done - in the cause of the - they 
a
ll liked dancing. And Mr Webb and Mr Aldridge used to say those boys want to learn you know and they haven't got any friends to teach them, anyone with any patience. Well, these girls evidently had lots of patience and they used to teach these boys and of
 course I used to go sometimes and that's how we met up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Your husband was one of these apprentices was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Mmm. He was my sisters pupil. And I took him away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 He was an apt pupil?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. Yes, we had one or two prizes for dancing. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What age were you when you met him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
I was nearly nineteen, because I remember going to one of these dances and it was my nineteenth birthday and I had a glass of port - the first time I'd ever tasted port wine - and he bought it in the interval - b
ecause it was my birthday. And it cost - it was at the club, you see, where he was a member of the club and he was allowed - I couldn't go and buy it - or anyone else - only members could buy drinks so that - I remember that very well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you like it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 I did - yes. And I might tell you that it was only sixpence a glass in those days - but it was good wine. Anyway I liked it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 He was from Waterstock wasn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, he was from Oxford. His father was a blacksmith at the University Press an
d all his brothers and uncles and grandfathers and all that were there, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 It was your father's family came from Waterstock was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, but he went to Waterstock when his mother - he was his mother's first child, you see. And when his moth
er was having the second child he was sent to aunties at Waterstock. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 
That's how Waterstock came in - and he - he went over there so many times while children were born and for other things as well - used to go over there - just spend a month with the aunti
es and he eventually went to school sometimes while he was over there you see and it was there that he acquired the habit of yes sir and no sir to the squire, you see, you all had to - because he was very fond of fishing and - he - going there one day and
 - you had to go and ask permission from the squire to go fishing. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You see his aunt made him go}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3757345\charrsid13250951 ,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  no you can't go fishing unless you ask the squire - so he had to go up to the big house to ask the squire. Because he said one day he - he met the squire as he 
was going up there and he said 'ah, I know what you're after, you young devil, you want to go fishing'. Squire Ashurst - he was a nice man. He was a gentleman. And a nice looking gentleman too.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you save up before getting married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. Oh
 we bought quite a bit of furniture at sales and things. We had very few new things when we were married - very few - but we had. - we bought several things beforehand you see. Chairs and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did your parents help you at all in setting up a home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Well, my mother gave us a bedstead and things like that. All secondhand. All what she didn't want you know - helped us out that way but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you have an engagement?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. We had an engagement - oh yes. For several years I was engaged. Yes, I 
was married when I was twenty-six - I suppose I had about a three year - three to four year engagement. Oh yes, you didn't get married as soon as you met anybody those days you know. We walked out together and got to know each other. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Could you describe the wedding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well of course it wasn't ....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you have many guests?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes. It was a wartime wedding but we had a - a wedding cake because - we had a - a friend who was a baker - he made us a sugar cake you see - it was - well, 
it wasn't quite so strict on the sugar and stuff in that - at 1916 - so we did have a proper wedding cake. Oh yes. And we had - a party - several - I had two bridesmaids and - we had a best man and then there were our parents and all our family and perhap
s
 just one or two special friends. But everybody came to the church and didn't expect to come on to the party afterwards all of them of course. It wasn't - it wasn't such a big elaborate affair. I had a nice white wedding dress - and a hat - I had a hat ma
de specially. I've got it - I've got a photograph somewhere of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 The reception was in your parents home was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Home - yes, at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you have a honeymoon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. Yes. We went to Southsea. And when we got there on the Saturday - w
e were married on the Saturday - August the fifth by the way - last week you see - when we got there - we went to the - lodgings - it - well, it was - they were sort of called apartment houses in those days you see, when we got there on the Saturday we fo
und that their daughter was being married on the Wednesday. So of course we had a whale of a time and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You went to the wedding did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Went to the wedding I think we did. And it was the place where they had - we'd stayed there two or three year
s before - we went with another couple for the first time and then we went on our own the next year and by the time - about another two years - they'd moved and they'd taken a shop. This man was a retired sailor who had a fish round with a }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 trolley}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  and that
 you know. Well then eventually he acquired this shop so his wife looked after the shop while he went on the round and therefore they gave up taking in people but as we'd been before they took us - I used to serve in the shop - serve the fish. But anyway 
w
hen we got down there Mary was being married on the Wednesday and so of course we had to muck in with everybody else and - I was serving in the shop right up 'til about eleven o'clock in the morning and - and my husband was doing all sorts of jobs and the
n
 they gave him the key - he was the last out. He had to wait behind while the bride and her father went, you see, and then lock up the shop and - come down to the chapel to the - to the wedding ceremony and I was already there you see with the mother and 
s
isters and that - I was right up in the front seat and I've never been to such a wet wedding in my life - everybody crying. And my husband - when he got down there you see, he was - he was right at the back - he had to sit on his own. But one funny thing 
about that wedding was - it was very, very nice}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3757345\charrsid13250951 ,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
 it was a very nice wedding - much more elaborate than ours but - very nice indeed and they had the reception in the hall underneath the chapel you see. And then, it was time the bridge and the groom went and 
- then it was time to take off - and they had all the wedding presents on display on the billiard table down there - then it was time you see to take all the stuff back to the house and they couldn't find the father. The father was going to fetch the trol
l
ey - his fish trolley - to take all the stuff back you see - it was all going to be boxed up and ready. Well, he went off with two of his old seamen pals to fetch the little horse and trolley and - they had to go to the stable you see, round to fetch Rosy
 
the pony's name was at the stable - fetch his trolley and come back to bring it. Well, we waited and waited and they didn't come back and Mrs Blake began to get a bit worried so she asked my husband to go up and hurry them up. Well, when he - when he got 
u
p there, there was the horse and trolley outside waiting for them, but the three old sailors inside were sat there drinking whisky. And he says he remembers persuading them to come down - 'course they'd all had a little drop to drink. And he remembers com
i
ng down Albert Road sitting on the back of that trolley and dangling his legs and laughing his head off - fetching these three men back. To fetch the stuff - then of course they packed all this - the remains of the wedding cake and things and all the pres
e
nts and - and we had a sort of little sing-song at night again and - that night we gave up our bed to a woman a - a woman with two children. My husband slept on the floor in the big room with two or three old sailors - 'course they didn't mind sleeping on
 
the floor, they were used to it - they'd missed the boat to go over to Gosport - back home, so we had to give up our bed. And I slept with Mrs Blake - with the mother. Suppose I slept, I don't know, don't remember much - but oh dear, we always laugh over 
that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 How long were you there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
A week - we had a week. And when it came to the end of the week and we were going to pay our lodgings you see - she wouldn't take anything - she gave it as a wedding present.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Because you'd been there three years before so you knew her quite well I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Yes, yes. Yes. Oh, I used to go and serve in the shop you see. My husband was always teasing her about - she used to come through the sitting room you see and bring the cash box and he'd say 'how much y
ou taken today, ma?' And we used to tease her and we always called - called her Mrs Golddust. Always. He - he gave her that nickname you see because of her cash box. And when she wrote to us at Christmas - which she did every Christmas for many years - sh
e always signed herself Mrs Golddust.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Where did you live when you got back to Oxford?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Well, we were promised a house you see, so we lived with my husbands people for three months - only three months - and then we had a nice little house, it was o
nly seven shillings a week - seven shillings a week and we paid the poor rate. I don't know why we had - yes, the poor rate was different to the ordinary rating like they rate them nowadays. But it was a nice little house - a very nice dry little house. T
h
at was in - Jericho - it isn't part with - that's being pulled down but it was off Walton Street - it was a small street at the bottom - only seven houses in it. And - it was a nice dry little house. But how we came to get that was - because of course you
 
could go round getting houses, but we'd never thought of sort of living there - we had no plans for any special place, but - talking to a man at the press one day - my husband you know saying we're getting - we're going to be married in August and - he sa
i
d 'have you got a house?' said this man. And he said no, why do you know of one? And - because we had been offered a house but on end of St. John's college. We were not ready to get married them and we sort of passed on the news to some friends of ours - 
a
nother apprentice with my husband - and they're still in the house today. On Kingston Road - that was a nice little house. But still - this other man - Mr Bowing - he said - have you got a house? And he said no, not at the moment - we're looking for one, 
w
hy do you know of one? And he said, well now - he said my wife's father's got a house which will shortly be going and he said one son wants it and the other son wants it and the daughter said she's going to have it. He said that would be one way of solvin
g the question he said if we gave it to a complete stranger. That's how we came to have it. And very glad of it too really.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 How old was your husband when you married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, I was twenty-six - he was going thirty - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What was his job then - he was at the press was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 He was a - printer - machine minder - printer, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And he'd finished his apprenticeship of course by then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. Yes. But he was coming - thirty-six shillings a week when we married and then - he used 
to got an extra two shillings a week when he took on an apprentice - a learner - to learn - to teach you see. And he had for that another two shillings a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did he do that work all his working life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. No, he was there and - he was there for
 quite a long time and - he had the urge to do something different and - some little upset came along - I hadn't tell you this perhaps. And he changed his job - yes. He went to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3757345\charrsid13250951 Morris\rquote 
s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did he ever leave }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3757345\charrsid13250951 Morris\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  and go anywhere else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, no. He retired from there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Was he doing printing there too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
No. No, he was on - on the line - on the assembly line. And enjoying it because he loved tools. Oh yes, he made all sorts of things. Well, you see, his father was a blacksmith and he was bro
ught up with tools. In fact, his father made the first bicycle that any of the children round Jericho over had. And made it out of gas piping and that sort of thing you know. Of course it was - it was a big treat - a bicycle in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 When he was at the press did he like the work or dislike it there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes, he liked the work - he liked the printing. He didn't like Shakespeare very much, he said. And he - remembers and used to talk about - you know, the different - you know, when they had to
 change the Bibles and prayer books and things as the Royalty - different Royalty died and so on. I remember when King Edward died - he did a lot of overtime then. We weren't married but - he had to work a lot of overtime - changing the Bible and that you
 see. And he was very good at his work I believe.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And you had a child - your first daughter was born in 1918 is that right?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What month was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 May. I'd been married a year and nine months when I had Dorothy and then there's a year and nine months between the two. So -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Was she born at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you know what to expect in childbirth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, I didn't very much and it turned out that she was a breach baby. But I had a nurse living opposite me and she w
as - she was not a district nurse - but - well she trained at Queen Charlotte}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3757345\charrsid13250951 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
s. She was a midwife who went to peoples houses for the month you know, to the better class people. I mean, I couldn't have afforded to have had her living in for a month and tha
t was the sort of job she used to go to. But she gave up her work to come home and look after her mother who was very ill, and - she was one of the first people who spoke to me when I - when we went to that house - she came across - I was cleaning the fro
n
t brass and she came across and introduced herself to me and she said - hoped - she hoped I'd be very happy and so on and so on you see. Well, then eventually when this baby was coming along - we were still very good friends - my - my husband used to do l
o
ts of odd jobs for her you know. He was very good at mending anything. And she'd come over and ask him to do this and do that - put a new plank in the floor or something like that and anyway - she asked me what I was going to do you see, about the baby. A
n
d I said well, I - I've been down to Doctor - Doctor Thompson and I guess I would have the district nurse. That's all there was in those days. And - she said she would come over and I believe her fee then - she was going to charge me about twenty-five shi
llings - and - anyway she came over and she attended me and she was wonderful. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You were pleased about that were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. And of course - living just opposite she naturally took an interest in us. But the second baby she was - she'd left
. Her mother had died and she'd left there and I had a district nurse.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 But with the first one you didn't have a doctor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. Oh yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 
Yes, I had a doctor and then I had - I had a little operation on the following Sunday - the baby was born on 
the Monday and - I'd had a fall - a bad fall - and - they decided that the afterbirth had grown to the side you see and it wouldn't all come away - I had to have a sort of an op - a scraping and - my own doctor - because he was all in Army uniform and eve
rything when he came and he brought another doctor - the underling and did it at home you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
And we had to borrow the table from the tap room at the pub opposite us and everything was cleared out of my bedroom you see and I do remember the other doctor wh
o came - I suppose I must have been a bit frightened or something - and I said to him - do you think my hearts all right, doctor? And he said - well, why shouldn't it be? That's what - I'd never had chloroform before. So he said well, we'll test it. But t
hen I had just the chloroform on a handkerchief. But anyway it was over they \{ILLEGIBLE\} this sister-in-law that I'm going with now - she took the baby out and nurse was there and my husband was there and - everything was all right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 How soon were you out of bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh not for three weeks.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you get up a little bit at a time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Yes, oh yes. Nurse was very particular with that - used to come over every day to wash and dress the baby every morning and then she'd come again in the evening. But
 she popped in any old time, you know, come in for a cup of tea sometimes when my husband came home from work. I had a sister-in-law came to stay and look after us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 When were you out of bed for the whole day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh, not until - quite a - a fortnigh
t - to sit out for the whole day. And it was three weeks before I was allowed downstairs. Of course it's very different \{ILLEGIBLE\}.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 How did you feed that first baby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh, I breast-fed both of them. For quite a long time until - second one - the
 second one I had to put her on the bottle after a while. But the first one I fed for about six months. Then she began to have spoon stuff you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did the first one ever have a bottle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Just a bottle to go to bed with at night and one bottle a day to supplement you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you enjoy feeding her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes. My mother - my mother persuaded me, as she persuaded all of us, because she used to say wherever you go you've got the babies feed - you never need worry about bottles and things like that. Wherever you go you've got it with you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you have any difficulties at all with the first one in feeding her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 It came quite easily?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Just - just came. Well, I suppose it was you see that I had my mother to sort of tell you
 what to do and - and persevere that was what she always what she used to say - you must persevere.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you have a routine or did you feed the baby simply when it seemed hungry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh no, you had proper times. And - my nurse - old Nurse }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 Darwin}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  - sh
e always used to say, now you want to sit down, make yourself comfortable, and put your feet up and give yourself plenty of time - don't hurry it - no, don't say oh well, and don't just sit anywhere. And if anyone was about you - you never fed your baby i
n front of them you know. You went into the other room - in privacy. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Had your mother been the same?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Yes, yes. We knew - we knew there were - that she fed the babies that way but - it was very seldom that we saw her actually feeding them, she would go either into her bedroom or into the front room for privacy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Was it certain feeding hours that you had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, yes. Every three hours - every four hours - whatever you decided on you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 If the baby woke before you were ready to feed it or before you thought it should be ready what did you do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, you just gave it a little drop of water - you had a little bottle then you see and gave it a little drop of water to - satisfy it.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 If the baby was asleep would you wake it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes. I used to but - my mother used to say I need not but - well with the first one we did - you - you're never so particular with the second one are you. It doesn't bother you so much - the second one. Just the first one you - you're worried abou
t it - naturally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 When you weaned the first one from the breast did you wean her suddenly or gradually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh, gradually you know, with soft foods and - potatoes and gravy and things like that - gradually came to - nothing of this patent food that 
they have nowadays although I think those things are very nice - all this patent stuff. And I read in the paper the other day where an old age pensioner said how - nice these baby foods were.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did the baby mind being weaned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, no, it didn't se
em to - just sort of graduated or - and then by - by the time they were twelve months they were just eating you know, ordinarily.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you think with your first one that it harmed a baby to leave it to cry or did you think it didn't matter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well,
 of course we didn't like them crying. And - I - I used to scold my husband 'cos he - he used to spoil the children - he thought they ought to be picked up }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 every time}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  they cried you know. Used to listen for them crying and - he would pick them up but - oh no, we used to let them cry a bit. Not too much of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you punish her if she was naughty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Well, not when they were tiny - no. You can - you can scold them and - I don't know, children seem to know don't they. They seem to know if you're 
- if you - are cross with them. I suppose we were like most mothers and fathers - we used to get cross if they cried in the night and - which of course they did the same as all children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did your husband do anything for the babies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. He wa
s too fussy, you know. Oh yes, he would - he would - always pick them up and walk round with them or anything like - never like some of the men do, wash the nappies and things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 He didn't change nappies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did he bath them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes
, he used to bath them. Oh yes, he was - used to bath her and he would always feed her - feed them. Oh yes. And take them out - always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did he take them in a pram?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. And you know when we came to live round here, you see our girls were - thirt
een and eleven when we came round here, and - the first estate was born next door to us here - the woman was expecting when we all moved in and that first baby was born in the April and her father never took her out in a pram or anything. We've got lots o
f snaps of my husband - he used to take her out - most Sunday mornings. Used to love babies and - and they were tiny - tiny babies - no matter how tiny they were. He just loved babies. But he used to take Doe out every Sunday morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 When you were first married how much of his earnings did he give to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Well, I don't remember that we had any special earnings - allotment made. I - I've still got the box there - in that desk - where I used to save - the rent.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You knew what your husband earned didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 It wasn't a secret or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
No, it was no secret. And he used to - I don't remember just how much we - we had but he used to have a few shilling for cigarettes which of course were quite cheap in those days -
 but we always put by so much money for the rent - so much for me, it was shilling in the slot gas in those days - no electric - and - so much for clothing and then the rent just went into the ordinary purse for food. And if he came home and wanted - if t
h
ere was anything different - like the paper papers - we used to have the daily paper - that was always paid for - he just had a few shillings in his pocket. I suppose out of our thirty shillings what did we do. We had seven shillings rent. Thirty-six shil
lings he had - I suppose he must have had three or four shillings a week in his pocket. But not much -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you discuss how the money should be spent?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. No, if one wanted anything we said well, you know, in the way of clothing - but usually mos
t people I think used to save up for clothing - you didn't just buy anything every week }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 haphazardly}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
 you see, you'd say well now, perhaps if we put so much a week by - half-a-crown a week or what have you, by Christmas we'll be - we'll have so much - we'll be able to buy certain things. There were always small things to buy for the children of course.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you continue to put money in at Capes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. Because Capes had a shop up near to where we lived you see. They had another department up there. A branch.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 They haven't got that any more have they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, that's gone now. But it hasn't been gone very many years. Yes, I still used to pay so much a week on a card up there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you make clothes for your daughters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, yes. Used to mak
e quite a lot. And my sisters were good to me you see, with their machines. And then one sister I had who used to knit a lot - the one that's just died. And she gave us lots of clothes for the children. They were very kind - very good to us. In fact - it 
i
sn't there - but I've got a picture oh it's upstairs - of them in two little dresses that my twin sister made - but they were very good with their needle you see. And - they made lots of clothes for the children. But I used to make the little petticoats a
nd - cut - I cut my wedding dress up for the children. Oh well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you take the shoes to a shoe maker or did your husband repair those?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well my husbands brother was a bootmaker - so we were fortunate that way. You see. And he would either repair
 them for us or give my husband the stuff }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 to repair}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
 them with himself or he would buy it from his brother you see. But he was a boot-maker as well as a mender.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You had nobody living with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. Well, yes, we had a - we had a blind man as a lod
ger. How my youngest girl was ten months when he came to us and how we had him - we'd no idea of ever having anyone living in our house. He lived with us - lived in with us you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You mentioned that you sent but his collars - would you also send out things of your husband and yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. I washed everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You washed at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. It was only these stiff collars you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you do all your own work? Did anyone help you at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did anyone ever come and take the babies for a walk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh the babies - yes. I used to have a little girl that would come and - you know and take the child out in the pram or - and like to do it and I think we used to give her about sixpence a week or a shilling or somethi
ng like that, you know, and have her - and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 have}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  her to tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 How often would she come?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh perhaps about twice a week - or Saturdays - she used to come Saturdays when she wasn't at school you see. Of course all the children used to love to come and take the babies out if they could but we didn't trust them with everybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 How many rooms were there in your house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh, it was an ordinary six roomed house. Quite a nice little house - very dry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Three bedrooms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Three bedrooms.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you have a parlour there -?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Yes, a front room and a living room and a kitchen - a nice kitchen we had - a nice little kitchen. And - a lavatory inside the house there too. And - well, when this blind man came to us you see I used to - I used to 
think I wouldn't be able to cape with a blind man but he was - one of the best people we ever had I think. And he used to go out to his club quite a bit - always home for meals - always home to time for meals.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you always have meals at a regular time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes. When my husband came home. You see, it used to be half past twelve from the University Press - he was at the University Press you see. So Mr .....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 When did you have your main meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Lunch - lunch time - mid-day - always cooked m
id-day meal. We all together you see, Mr Smith would come home in time for the meal - and he'd always be there - ready. Very considerate in every way. And then they decided that - the blind people would help him and they sent a teacher.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you make bread or jam or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Always made jam. No, I never made bread until I came up here and the woman who lived next door was a Yorkshire woman and she taught me how to make bread.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you do any pickling?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. Everybody did the pickles and jam.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you make wine and beer at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. My husbands mother did, but I didn't do that until we came up here - well, until we moved from Jericho and then ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you have a garden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 My husband had an allotment because du
ring the first world war you see the Port Readow was cut up as allotments. So while we were there, living in Jericho, he had an allotment - and we grew wonderful stuff there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you ever need to buy any vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh, very little. After he got the allotment you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What about fruit - did you have any fruit growing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
No, no. But you could always buy if you lived anywhere near say a man who worked on the railway or - an engine driver or something like that - and they had the run throug
h to Evesham they could buy what they called a pot of plums which was - forty pounds. And then - they called it a pot of plums - yes - a big basket which held forty pounds - and they would always sell you some you see. They got them quite cheaply. Going t
hrough the market garden - at Evesham where they produce them you see. They would be able to buy them quite cheaply. And then they would share them with their neighbours and sell them you see. They'd get their money back - that way.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 How many times a week did you eat meat when you were first married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh, most days. We didn't ....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you have tinned meat at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. Very little. Very little. We - we just only managed butchers meat or bacon - a piece of boiled bacon you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What about extra meat? You remember you told me about the crayfish that came from Blenheim?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh well, we didn't then, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you have any poached food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 I had - I had an occasional rabbit. And once I had a pleasant which I thought was wonderful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you buy that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, my brother-in-law - he wasn't my brother-in-law then - my sister hadn't married then - but he - he was a poacher.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 And he gave it to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. Yes, he often used to come and ask for a bed you see. If he - he lived 
out Chadbury - Finstock way you see and if he had occasion to come into Oxford and stay the night - or wanted to stay the night - he would always bring us a rabbit or something like that. But then you see you could buy a rabbit for about one and six. In t
hose days. Oh we fed very well really. Very well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you ever go away for a holiday after you were married up to the end of the first war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. We had our first seaside holiday when we'd been married ten years. And we went to Bournemouth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you go out visiting and seeing friends and relations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 
Well, no, I used - I had a bicycle in those days and I used to have to pop up and down to my mother and - just along that time the first two or three years of our marriage she was pretty ill wit
h a poisoned hand and I used to have to take her - well, I took her to the hospital in the first place and then I think I told you about Doctor Stansfield that had the surgery opposite - used to take her over there every day for the doctor and - just hold
 her while she had it done. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 She had to have it - her thumb drained and didn't like the idea of going up to the hospital - and Doctor Stansfield used to do it for her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you go and see anyone else - any friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. We had - we had our siste
rs and that you see to go to and that - married sisters and - and they used to come down to us. And different friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you have friends - you mentioned you went on holiday with another couple - did you still ....?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes - we're still friend
s now - had a card from them only this week - they're at Clacton-on-Sea - that's the people we let have the house, you see. Nice house too - but still - they've been very happy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you get together with them when you were married?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Very - no we
 didn't go out very - a lot after we - when we had the babies small - we used to go out to tea and take the children but - not go anywhere much. Unless it was to - things connected with the University Press - my husband was a fireman there you see and the
y used to have the - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 fire brigade}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
 competitions and things like that and we all used to meet at those sort of social - they were about the only social things. Or if they had amateur theatricals at the Institute we'd go along there you see. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What Institute?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
The Clarendon Press Institute - we'd go along and if it was in the evening you see one of my sisters would come along and sit with the children - I'd put them to bed and that would allow us to go out together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you ever have any other baby sitters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, generally our own people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you stop going to church then or did you continue?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh no. We used to go to St }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 Barnabus}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  church - but not very often because we didn't like the Vicar, very much. And then the children you see
 - as the children - five years old they went to school - the second one went when she was four because she bothered so much to go because Dorothy went to school and she had to go. Yes, so she had to go a little bit earlier and then you see there were alw
ays the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 children's}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  parties and the - those sort of things and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you go out on Bank Holidays with the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. Generally. One of our favourite walks used to be up and through Boar's Hill. We used to take the children down to the grandmot
hers you see and perhaps have our dinner down there with them on a Bank Holiday and then go for a walk through the woods and things and back again - back home for a late tea and so on. Oh yes, we always took the children out or my husband would sometimes 
say he'd like to go fishing so he used to go fishing up the side of Medley river then we used to go up afterwards and take tea and sit there with him - nothing very special you know but we enjoyed it of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did he do anything else besides fishing in the way of recreation? Go and watch football or ....?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes, he used to like to watch football. He used to play it in his young days - but not after we were married. No, he was a very }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 home loving}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  man - he didn't want to be out without us much - no. W
e had some friends at Wolvercote - a woman that I used - had worked with at the shop and then she eventually married a man with four children - his wife died and she went and - and we used to visit them up there and all the children played together you kn
ow, in the hay fields. He was a man who had some fields and small holdings and that an used to go up to Aunty }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 Mabel's}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
 as we called it and take tea down the hay fields for the men. Get up to all sorts of mischief, you know, the children used to. Once they had one of the horses fell in the ditch, and of course that was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 marvellous}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  for children to see the horse pulled out of the ditch. Then Dorothy and one of the boys from up there fell off the top of a haystack. Oh dear.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 But your husband didn't go to the races?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did he go to the pub for a drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. Never drank. He - in later years he used to like whisky wine and stuff like that but he never drunk beer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What about you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, no, I never drunk beer. We never went to pubs as - 
as a pub, you know. If we were out on a holiday or - if we'd gone for a long walk we would call in at a country pub and have a glass of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3757345\charrsid13250951 cider}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  or something like that. And when we were courting - when we used to go out on our bicycles - we would stop at a place and have a glass of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3757345\charrsid13250951 cider}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  but we neither of us drank beer.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 When you had meals did you may grace when you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, we started when the children were small but I'm sorry to say we - they never kept it up after they were about twelv
e or thirteen. But they did used to say, as my brothers always said, my - you know my brothers when they ca}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3757345\charrsid13250951 me home dirty from the traction}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  engines and they had their meal - they never moved from the table without saying - thank God for my good dinner. And 
- I can hear my brothers saying it now. And my children used to say that after - after stopping saying their proper grace as we - I suppose we got a bit careless about it you see - but they always said thank God for my good dinner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Was your husband interested in politics in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, I can't say that he was - he joined this - they had to join the trades union you see, and they - and he belonged to the }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1320587\charrsid13250951 Oddfellows}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  - he went through the chairs as they call it at the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795503\charrsid13250951 O}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1320587\charrsid13250951 ddfellows}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 . He was interested in that. And, ....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you know what his views were - what way he was inclined?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
No, I can't say - but not labour. He - yes, he was either Liberal or Conservative he wasn't a Labour man. I used to hear him talk about the other man, you know, ah, he's a proper Labour man. I thought, well evidently you're not, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 But you don't know which one he was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. I think we generally voted Conservative. I think so. But - I've always been at the - idea that you don't want to vote for a pa
rty - you want to vote for the person - yes. Especially in municipal affairs. I always vote for the person never mind his politics.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you remember voting in a general election - there was one in 1918 when women had the vote I think - do you remember voting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
We had a - we had a general - the first general election I can remember after I was married was when a Mr Frank Gray - a big - very popular Liberal got in. He was - he became our member of parliament and then - by some quirk of fate he was tu
rned out because - someone had decided that he had been bribing people - whether it was ever true or not I don't know but it - smashed him up you know. That was that was the Liberal candidate. But - the first people I can remember Cons - when I - when we 
had to vote - was a Captain Bore. That was a Conservative man here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you know if your husband was ever under any pressure to vote for a certain party because of his employers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. No, there was nothing of that in those days. They - he did belon
g to the trades union but he - he had to belong to the union you see - the printers union. The printers union - the typographical association it was called in those days. And unfortunately he paid in for many, many years which would have entitled him to a
 
pound a week - superannuation - and then again some argument you see, that was all washed out. And all he was paid out was nine pound after having to pay in for a number of years. It sort of shook his faith in trade unions a bit. But of course he had to b
elong to it. When he was working at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3757345\charrsid13250951 Morris\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  - oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Was he a member of a political party at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Do you ever remember him working for elections?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No. No. Never interested that way. The only interest was these - this friendly 
society you see - the Oddfellows and - he did go through the chairs in that. And .....
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 You mentioned that he liked fishing and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did he have any hobbies in the home that he used to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 He used to do a lot of
 fretwork and, as I say, he was very useful with tools. And he'd put you up a shelf or make you a little table or stool or something like that you know. And - always see that everything worked - he used to go round Sunday mornings with a feather and a bot
t
le of oil - make all the latches work and all the window latches - anything that should work did work. I miss all that you see now. Yes. He - as a matter of fact that dresser stood out quite a bit more than that and he took all that down and set it back. 
And put it back level you see with the - not the top part - this bottom part. It used to stand out another six inches or so and he put it back level. Things like that you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did he like reading?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Yes. But - he would only read - like when the ev
enings got darker - as long is it was light he was amusing himself in the garden or with tools - he had lots of tools which I've had to give all away, you know. And everything - he made everything work you know. He'd take a door off and make it work prope
rly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 When you were first married did you read?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Not a great deal. Well we used to have the ordinary little }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1320587\charrsid13250951 tuppenny}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  weekly papers and things you know. That we passed on -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Local papers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Nothalls}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1320587\charrsid13250951  (?)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951  and things like that that girls passed on to another, you know. I can't remember ever buying any, but we ....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you have a daily paper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Yes, we had a daily paper. And - of later years of course I've belonged to the Library. The public library - and always had - and the girls too - and - well my husband did. We used to have books. I still do, from the library.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Can you remember about bringing up your children? When your children were very small did you feel that there was a right way and a wrong way of bringing up children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Well, only that - we brought them up to - be respectful to everybody and to do - to do as they were told and be polite and - and they - certain - they were always brought up to - well, you must go down to see your grandma - you know - and never neglect a
nybody because they're old you must go and look after them and - now if you go down to grandma's and she asks you to go an errand for her you go. And they - they were always willing to go. They were never - they were never children that said - no, I'm, no
t
 going unless you give me a penny - like some children were. They never expected to be paid for what they did. You see, if I said to them when they came home from school - oh Dorothy I forgot to get so and so - just run round to - we had all sorts of shop
s
 round by us you see - go round to Mr Collins will you or if we might have wanted some extra milk and he sold milk - this man - although we had a milkman call every day you see, but perhaps I would use more and I'd want a little extra and when they came i
n from school and I asked them, I - I want you to go to Mr Collins to get so and so - there was never any query about it. Always - they went - it was - it was what they were asked to do and that was it, see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you and your husband have the same attitude to bringing up children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh yes. We never interfered with each other. If one corrected - it was left at that you see. I never said no don't do that if he'd said do it. And he was the same with us. Oh no, we never interfered - in any way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 If you were worried about the children who would you talk to about it? Was there anyone you could talk to if you were worried about them?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Well, only our own parents and sisters and that you know. I had some ....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you get advice from your mother about the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. Oh yes, we always went to our mothers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 What about your mother-in-law?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Yes. We - I had a good mother-in-law. She taught me to cook - yes. She was a cook. She paid for training to be a cook at Christ Church. Christ Church College she went to in the kitchens there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 When you were first married couldn't you cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 No, I couldn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Your mother had always done it had she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. And - you see my father used to do quite a lot of the cooking too and 
he didn't want any of us interfering so that although we - we knew just the ordinary rudiments of cooking but you - you couldn't say we were anything special in the way of cooking. If my husband were here today he'd tell you about my first pastry. He alwa
y
s says it's a concrete path for somebody. Well, you see, that first house we had was an ordinary open grate with the oven at the side, I think I told you my mother had one. Well, I made - the first lot of pastry I ever made I put it in this oven and I did
n
't know that I had to pull a damper out at the top to let the flame go under the oven you see - therefore we had concrete instead of pastry. Well, we always laughed over it anyway - and he said you know how to make a good concrete path he said. I never li
ved it down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 When would your children have a bath when they were little?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh, practically every night. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 It wasn't the weekly bath then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh no. It wasn't like us. You see, we had more facilities. We had a nice little kitchen place an
d - and I had - yes, I had running water inside - and I had a copper there that I could always pop on. I - I generally had a copper on twice a week for washing you see, and I had a very big bath. Well, that used to be brought into the living room on the t
a
ble or onto a stool at the side and the children bathed in front of the fire. Oh, most nights really - and washed and put to bed nice and clean. My mother always used to say to me - if you bath those children at night you know they sleep ever so much swee
ter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 When did they have clean clothes to put on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 
Oh, two and three times a week, you see. I mean they generally a fresh pair of knickers every day because they used to sit about - coming in from school and sit on the step. Sit on the back step or
 a little stool out there - oh yes. Well, you were always washing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6563310 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Did you think it was important to show children affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10158830 EG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14492107\charrsid13250951 Oh yes. Yes, we loved them. And my husband especially. He would sing to them, well, we've always sung at home quite a l
ot - when we were all girls together you know and I - and I - no doubt it was the brothers working at the theatre and us having these musical scores and things you see we used to teach ourselves all the - we know all the musical plays. And it just - it ju
s
t came sort of automatically if we were there all together - five or six of us girls - someone would start singing and then we would all join in. We - used to have lovely times really. And my husband used to sing a lot - he played the piano. And - we didn
'
t have a piano for years after we were married but we did have one eventually and both the girls were taught. But - we used to sing quite a lot. And he was very fond of sitting down cuddling the children and singing to them. We had a very happy life. Very
 happy indeed.
